const a = [
  {"id":3566,"text":"A 13-year-old female presents to the outpatient department (OPD) with on and off menorrhagia, bleeding gums, and petechial rashes. Her laboratory reports show the following results; Hb= 12.5 g/dl, platelet count= 350,000/mm3, activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT)= 49s (normal: 29-40s). Which of the following could be the likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The likely diagnosis for the 13-year-old female with on and off **menorrhagia, bleeding gums**, and **petechial rashes**, along with an **elevated activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT)**, is **von Willebrand disease**.\r\n\r\nVon Willebrand disease is a bleeding disorder characterized by a deficiency or dysfunction of **von Willebrand factor (vWF)**, a protein involved in platelet adhesion and clot formation. The symptoms often include mucocutaneous bleeding, such as nosebleeds, easy bruising, heavy or prolonged menstrual bleeding, and bleeding gums.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the normal platelet count and hemoglobin level make iron deficiency anemia less likely as a diagnosis. Anemia of chronic disease is also less likely as it typically presents with lower hemoglobin levels. Immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP) typically presents with isolated thrombocytopenia and does not cause prolonged aPTT. Thrombotic microangiopathy usually presents with signs of microvascular thrombosis and associated organ damage, which are not described in this case.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 662.","responses":[{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anemia of chronic disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"von Willebrand disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombotic microangiopathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4269,"text":"Where are most of the body's iron reserves found?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 891.","responses":[{"text":"Ferritin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemosiderin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haptoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4414,"text":"Which of the following is the best test for the diagnosis of malaria?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 391.","responses":[{"text":"Microbiological culture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thick and thin film","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Serologic test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enzyme-linked immunoassay (ELISA) test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pap smear","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10074,"text":"A 13-year-old girl falls and hits her head on the wall, leading to trauma of the blood vessels. Tissue thromboplastin will be released by the endothelial cells. Which of the following factors will be involved in initiating coagulation?","explanation":"When tissue thromboplastin is exposed to circulating **Factor VII**, it binds to the tissue factor and forms a complex. This complex, along with calcium ions, activates Factor X to its active form, Factor Xa. Factor Xa then acts as a catalyst in the common pathway of coagulation, leading to the formation of a fibrin clot.\r\n\r\nIt's important to note that the intrinsic pathway is not involved in this initial phase of coagulation following trauma. Factors IX, XII, and HMWK are part of the intrinsic pathway, which is primarily activated by contact with negatively charged surfaces. In this case, the trauma to the blood vessels triggers the extrinsic pathway.\r\n\r\nReference: Hall JE, Guyton AC. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th edition. Elsevier, 2021.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 481.","responses":[{"text":"High-molecular-weight kininogen (HMWK)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VII","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor IX","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor V","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor XII","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10092,"text":"Which of the following components are involved in the first step of heme synthesis?","explanation":"The synthesis of heme, a vital molecule for the formation of hemoglobin, begins with the condensation of **succinyl CoA and glycine**. This reaction is catalyzed by the enzyme aminolevulinic acid synthase (ALAS). The resulting product, aminolevulinic acid (ALA), is a key intermediate in the heme synthesis pathway.\r\n\r\nALAS is the rate-limiting enzyme in heme synthesis and its activity is regulated by various factors, including the availability of succinyl CoA and glycine. Succinyl CoA is derived from the citric acid cycle, while glycine is an amino acid. Together, they provide the building blocks for the initial step of heme synthesis.","reference":"(1) Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 278\r\n\r\n(2) Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 235","responses":[{"text":"Malonyl CoA and glycine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Succinyl CoA and glycine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Malonyl CoA and serine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Succinyl CoA and serine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10146,"text":"Which antibody has a pentameric structure?","explanation":"Among the different classes of antibodies (immunoglobulins), **IgM** is the antibody that has a pentameric structure. IgM is the first antibody produced during the primary immune response and plays a crucial role in the early stages of an infection.\r\n\r\nThe pentameric structure of IgM consists of five monomeric subunits joined together by a J (joining) chain and disulfide bonds. This unique structure allows IgM to have multiple antigen-binding sites, enhancing its ability to bind to pathogens and facilitate their removal from the body.\r\n\r\nThe large size and pentameric structure of IgM contribute to its efficient functioning in the immune response. It enables IgM to effectively agglutinate (clump together) antigens, activate complement system components, and facilitate phagocytosis by macrophages.\r\n\r\nWhile other antibody classes, such as IgG, IgA, IgD, and IgE, exist as monomers or dimers, IgM stands out for its pentameric structure, making it highly effective in the early stages of immune defense.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 103.","responses":[{"text":"IgA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgG","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgE","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgD","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgM","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12621,"text":"A 7-year-old boy developed vesicles and bullae on his face and arms due to prolonged sun exposure from participating in sports activities. His father had a similar condition. He is suspected of porphyria cutanea tarda. Which of the following enzymes is mainly deficient in the above-mentioned disease condition?","explanation":"In porphyria cutanea tarda (PCT), the main enzyme deficiency is **uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase**.\r\n\r\nUroporphyrinogen decarboxylase is an enzyme involved in the heme biosynthesis pathway. It catalyzes the conversion of uroporphyrinogen III to coproporphyrinogen III, which is a crucial step in the synthesis of heme. Heme is an essential component of hemoglobin and other heme-containing proteins.\r\n\r\nIn individuals with PCT, there is a deficiency of uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase, leading to the accumulation of uroporphyrinogen III and its derivatives in the liver and other tissues. This accumulation is triggered by factors such as exposure to sunlight, alcohol consumption, and certain medications.\r\n\r\nThe excess uroporphyrinogen III and its derivatives are photosensitive and can be activated by sunlight, resulting in the formation of reactive oxygen species and damage to the skin. This manifests as vesicles, bullae, and skin fragility, particularly in sun-exposed areas.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 280.","responses":[{"text":"Uroporphyrinogen carboxylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uroporphyrinogen dehydratase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uroporphyrinogen deaminase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Uroporphyrinogen synthase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12628,"text":"Which of the following is the region in the primary structure of immunoglobulins that determines the antibody class?","explanation":"The primary structure of immunoglobulins, also known as antibodies, consists of two types of chains: **heavy chains** and **light chains**. Each chain has a **variable region** and a **constant region**. The variable regions of both heavy and light chains contribute to the **antigen-binding site** of the antibody, providing specificity for **antigen recognition**.\r\n\r\nHowever, it is the constant region of the heavy chain that determines the **antibody class or isotype**. The constant region of the heavy chain determines the effector functions and other characteristics of the antibody, such as its ability to activate complement, cross the placenta, or bind to specific cell receptors. There are five main antibody classes or isotypes: IgM, IgG, IgA, IgD, and IgE, and each class has a distinct constant region of the heavy chain.","reference":"Charles A Janeway J, Travers P, Walport M, Shlomchik MJ. The structure of a typical antibody molecule. Immunobiology: The Immune System in Health and Disease. 5th edition. Published 2001. Accessed December 9, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK27144/","responses":[{"text":"Variable region of heavy chain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Constant region of heavy chain","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Constant region of light chain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypervariable region of light chain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Variable region of light chain","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12630,"text":"C-reactive protein, which is elevated in case of inflammation and infection, falls into the category of which of the following plasma proteins?","explanation":"**C-reactive protein (CRP)** falls into the category of **acute phase proteins**.\r\n\r\nAcute phase proteins are a group of proteins that are produced by the liver in response to inflammation, infection, or tissue injury. They are part of the innate immune response and play a role in the early stages of the body's defense mechanisms. CRP is one of the major acute phase proteins and its levels increase rapidly in response to inflammation or infection. Elevated levels of CRP can be seen in various conditions, including bacterial and viral infections, tissue injury, autoimmune diseases, and certain cancers. CRP levels can be measured through a blood test and are used as a marker of inflammation in clinical practice.","reference":"Sproston NR, Ashworth JJ. Role of c-reactive protein at sites of inflammation and infection. Frontiers in Immunology. Published April 13, 2018. Accessed November 23, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5908901/","responses":[{"text":"Transport proteins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma enzymes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oncotic proteins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute phase proteins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Clotting proteins","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13003,"text":"A 55-year-old man was diagnosed with constrictive pericarditis, two years after suffering from trauma to the heart. When he died an autopsy was performed. The heart was encased in a thickened, fibrotic pericardium. The pericardium was attached to the heart by a stingy material that was difficult to remove. What type of inflammation did the patient have in his pericardium?","explanation":"**Fibrinous inflammation** is characterized by the exudation of **fibrin-rich fluid** into the affected tissue or body cavity. It typically occurs in response to severe injury or inflammation and is associated with increased vascular permeability and the leakage of fibrinogen into the affected area. The fibrinogen is then converted into fibrin, forming a meshwork that can adhere to the tissue surfaces and create adhesions.\r\n\r\nIn the case of the patient with **constrictive pericarditis**, the thickened and fibrotic pericardium that encased the heart suggests the presence of chronic inflammation. The formation of adhesions between the pericardium and the heart indicates the involvement of fibrinous inflammation.","reference":"Bhatti R, Sonani B, Dhamoon AS. Fibrinous pericarditis. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed December 6, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538254/","responses":[{"text":"Purulent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Catarrhal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinous","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13007,"text":"A 65-year-old woman is being treated for pain and inflammation in her joints for the past year. Which of the following statements regarding the patient's inflammation is correct?","explanation":"**Chronic inflammation**, as described in the scenario, is characterized by the simultaneous presence of inflammation, tissue destruction, and attempts at tissue repair. Unlike acute inflammation, which is typically characterized by a neutrophilic infiltrate, chronic inflammation involves the **infiltration of mononuclear cells such as lymphocytes and macrophages**. Abscess formation is not a characteristic feature of chronic inflammation. \r\n\r\nGranuloma formation, which consists of aggregates of epithelioid cells (not epithelial cells), giant cells, and lymphocytes surrounded by a rim of fibroblasts and collagen, is a possible outcome of chronic inflammation but is not mentioned in the given scenario.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 96.","responses":[{"text":"It always follows the acute inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is predominantly characterized by a neutrophilic infiltrate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abscess formation is the hallmark","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It may result in granulomas composed of epithelial cells and blood vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It involves co-existence of inflammation, tissue repair and attempts at repair","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13011,"text":"An individual sprains their ankle while hiking in the mountains and it becomes inflamed. Which of the following statements is most correct regarding this type of inflammation?","explanation":"**Inflammation** is a normal response of the body to injury or infection, and it is characterized by these classic signs and symptoms: **heat** (due to increased blood flow), **redness** (due to vasodilation), pain (caused by chemical mediators and pressure on nerve endings), and **swelling** (resulting from increased vascular permeability and fluid accumulation). These symptoms are part of the inflammatory process and are commonly observed in cases of sprains, where there is tissue damage and an inflammatory response is initiated to facilitate healing.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 12.","responses":[{"text":"It is characterized heat, redness, pain and swelling","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It resolves within twenty-four hours","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The cellular infiltrate comprises of macrophages and lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is not associated with tissue damage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is characterized by the formation of granulomas","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13050,"text":"The blood remains in circulation because of a balance between procoagulant and anticoagulant forces. Proteolytic destruction of which of the following by the protein C inhibits the process of coagulation?","explanation":"**Proteolytic destruction** of activated **factor V** and **factor VIII** by **protein C** inhibits the process of coagulation. Protein C is a **natural anticoagulant** protein that works in conjunction with its cofactor **protein S** to inactivate **factors Va and VIIIa**, which are important for the amplification of the coagulation cascade. By cleaving activated factor V and factor VIII, protein C helps to downregulate the coagulation process and prevent excessive clot formation. This mechanism serves as an important negative feedback loop to maintain the balance between coagulation and anticoagulation in the bloodstream.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 483.","responses":[{"text":"Activated factor VII and factor X","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activated factor V and factor VIII","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Activated factor I and factor IV","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activated factor X and factor XI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activated factor II and factor III","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13058,"text":"Which of the following terms best describes the occurrence of a disease in a community or region with a frequency clearly in excess of normal expectancy?","explanation":"An **epidemic** refers to the rapid spread of a disease within a population or geographical area, resulting in a higher number of cases than expected. It indicates a sudden increase in the incidence of a particular disease beyond what is typically seen in that population or area. Epidemics can be localized or widespread, affecting a specific community, region, or even multiple countries.\r\n\r\nExotic refers to a disease that is foreign or not native to a particular region or population.\r\nEndemic describes the constant presence or usual prevalence of a disease within a specific geographic area or population.\r\nPandemic refers to a global outbreak of a disease, affecting a large number of people worldwide.\r\nSporadic refers to isolated cases of a disease occurring occasionally and without any pattern or regularity.","reference":"https://www.cdc.gov/csels/dsepd/ss1978/lesson1/section11.html","responses":[{"text":"Sporadic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidemic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Exotic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pandemic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13059,"text":"Which of the following terms best describes the disease causation model that can be used for explaining the mechanism of chronic disease occurrence like diabetes and heart disease with multiple risk factors?","explanation":"The term that best describes the disease causation model used to explain the mechanism of chronic disease occurrence with multiple risk factors is the **web of causation**. The web of causation model recognizes that chronic diseases, such as diabetes and heart disease, are multifactorial in nature and result from the complex interaction of multiple risk factors. These risk factors can include genetic predisposition, lifestyle factors (such as diet and physical activity), environmental factors, and social determinants of health. The web of causation model illustrates how these various factors interact and contribute to the development of chronic diseases, emphasizing the interconnectedness and complexity of the causal pathways involved.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Blood Module; Subject: Community medicine; Topic: Origin and determinants of disease; Sub-topic: The web of causation.","responses":[{"text":"Wheel of causation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidemiological triangle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Web of causation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Determinants of disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dynamics of disease transmission","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13451,"text":"The complement system is a system of about 20 different proteins which perform important defensive functions in the body. there are three pathways of complement activation, classical pathway, alternate pathway, and mannose-binding lecithin pathway. These pathways merge at which of the following stages?","explanation":"The three pathways of complement activation, namely the classical pathway, alternative pathway, and lectin pathway, converge at the **activation of C3b**. C3b is a central component of the complement system and plays a crucial role in the **opsonization of pathogens, phagocytosis**, and the **formation of the membrane attack complex (MAC)** to destroy target cells. Once C3b is activated, it initiates a cascade of reactions that lead to the formation of MAC and the subsequent destruction of the target cell.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 537.","responses":[{"text":"Activation of C5a","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Breakdown of C1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of C3b","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Formation of the membrane attack complex (MAC)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of C7","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15337,"text":"A 45-year-old woman develops swelling in her lower legs and feet after standing for long periods at the end of her 8-hour shift with no associated pain or erythema. There is no swelling at the beginning of her day. Her kidney and liver are also in healthy condition. What is the probable diagnosis for her condition?","explanation":"**Heart failure** can lead to impaired pumping function of the heart, resulting in reduced cardiac output and increased venous pressure. The increased venous pressure leads to fluid accumulation in the dependent areas, such as the lower extremities.\r\n\r\nHeart failure can be caused by various factors, including coronary artery disease, hypertension, valvular heart disease, and cardiomyopathies. It is important to evaluate the patient for signs and symptoms of heart failure, such as dyspnea, fatigue, orthopnea, and peripheral edema.\r\n\r\nOther causes of lower extremity swelling, such as renal insufficiency, arthritis, nephritic syndrome, and gout, would typically present with additional symptoms and findings specific to those conditions. In this case, the absence of pain, erythema, and involvement of kidney and liver function helps differentiate heart failure as the likely cause of the swelling.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 117.","responses":[{"text":"Increased hydrostatic pressure due to heart failure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gout","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephritic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal insufficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arthritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15344,"text":"Which is the characteristic morphology of red blood cells seen in megaloblastic anemia?","explanation":"In megaloblastic anemia, which is typically caused by deficiencies in vitamin B12 or folic acid, the characteristic morphology of red blood cells includes **macro-ovalocytes**. Macro-ovalocytes are abnormally large and oval-shaped red blood cells.\r\n\r\nNormally, red blood cells are round and of uniform size. However, in megaloblastic anemia, impaired DNA synthesis and delayed maturation of red blood cell precursors result in the production of larger and more oval-shaped cells.\r\n\r\nThe presence of macro-ovalocytes can be observed on a peripheral blood smear, which is a microscopic examination of a blood sample. This finding is an important diagnostic clue for megaloblastic anemia. Other features that may be seen in megaloblastic anemia include hypersegmented neutrophils, anemia, and abnormalities in other blood cell lineages.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 651.","responses":[{"text":"Heinz bodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macro-ovalocyte","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypersegmented neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Central pallor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle-shaped red blood cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15345,"text":"Which is the characteristic morphology of white blood cells seen in megaloblastic anemia?","explanation":"In megaloblastic anemia, which is typically caused by deficiencies in vitamin B12 or folic acid, the characteristic morphology of white blood cells includes **hypersegmented neutrophils**. Neutrophils are a type of white blood cell that plays a crucial role in the immune response and defense against infections.\r\n\r\nHypersegmented neutrophils are identified by the presence of more than five nuclear lobes. In normal individuals, neutrophils typically have two to five lobes. However, in megaloblastic anemia, due to impaired DNA synthesis and delayed nuclear maturation, the neutrophils exhibit hypersegmentation.\r\n\r\nThe appearance of hypersegmented neutrophils serves as an important clue in the diagnosis of megaloblastic anemia. Other findings in megaloblastic anemia may include macrocytic red blood cells, anemia, and abnormalities in other blood cell lineages.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 651.","responses":[{"text":"Heinz bodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polymorphonuclear neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophilic stippling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypersegmented neutrophils","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Megaovalocyte","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15888,"text":"A child gets a micro-cut on his finger while playing with a razor. The wound stops bleeding shortly after. Which of the following mechanisms is primarily responsible for this?","explanation":"The primary mechanism responsible for the cessation of bleeding in the child's micro-cut wound is **platelet plug formation**. Platelets, also known as thrombocytes, are small cell fragments in the blood that play a crucial role in hemostasis. When a blood vessel is injured, platelets adhere to the exposed collagen in the damaged vessel wall. This adhesion is facilitated by von Willebrand factor and other adhesive molecules.\r\n\r\nOnce adhered, platelets become activated and undergo shape change, releasing granules containing various substances such as ADP and thromboxane A2. These substances further recruit and activate more platelets, leading to the formation of a platelet plug at the site of injury. The platelet plug acts as a temporary seal to prevent further blood loss from the injured vessel.\r\n\r\nWhile vasoconstriction, the intrinsic and extrinsic pathways of coagulation, and fibrin formation are also important components of hemostasis, in the context of the child's micro-cut wound, platelet plug formation is the primary mechanism responsible for stopping the bleeding.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 478.","responses":[{"text":"Fibrin formation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasoconstriction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extrinsic pathway","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelet plug formation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intrinsic pathway","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15957,"text":"If the set point for diabetes mellitus in a population was 105 mg/dL and the researcher dropped it to 100 mg/dL. What will be the change in sensitivity and specificity?","explanation":"In the context of diagnostic testing, sensitivity and specificity are measures of the test's performance in correctly identifying individuals with a particular condition and correctly identifying individuals without the condition, respectively.\r\n\r\nIf the **set point** for diabetes mellitus is **lowered** from 105 mg/dL to 100 mg/dL, it means that the threshold for diagnosing diabetes has become **more stringent**. This change will lead to an **increase in sensitivity** and a **decrease in specificity**.\r\n\r\n**Sensitivity** is the ability of a test to correctly identify individuals who have the disease (true positive rate). By lowering the threshold, some individuals who were previously considered negative for diabetes may now be classified as positive, increasing sensitivity.\r\n\r\n**Specificity** is the ability of a test to correctly identify individuals who do not have the disease (true negative rate). With a more stringent cutoff, individuals without diabetes who previously fell below the threshold may now be classified as (false) positive, leading to a decrease in specificity.","reference":"Trevethan R. Sensitivity, specificity, and predictive values: foundations, pliabilities, and pitfalls in research and practice. Frontiers in Public Health. 2017;5. Accessed May 26, 2023. https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpubh.2017.00307","responses":[{"text":"Sensitivity increases but specificity decreases","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Only sensitivity increases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sensitivity decreases but specificity increases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No change in sensitivity or specificity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Only sensitivity decreases","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16146,"text":"Which one of the following types of cells starts their existence in the bone marrow, and gives rise to all blood cells on its own?","explanation":"**Pluripotent hematopoietic stem cells** (PHSC) start their existence in the bone marrow. These cells have the potential to differentiate into various specialized cell types within the hematopoietic system. This includes red blood cells (erythrocytes), white blood cells (leukocytes), and platelets.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nColony-forming unit-spleen (CFU-S) are committed progenitor cells specifically dedicated to forming lymphocytes in the spleen. \r\n\r\nColony-forming unit-erythrocytes (CFU-E) and proerythroblasts can only generate erythrocytes.\r\n\r\nColony-forming unit-blast is not a specific term for a particular cell type in the hematopoietic hierarchy.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 440.","responses":[{"text":"Colony-forming unit-blast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pluripotent hematopoietic stem cell","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Colony-forming unit-spleen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proerythroblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colony-forming unit-erythrocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16147,"text":"Why is blood classified as a special connective tissue?","explanation":"**Blood** is classified as a **special connective tissue** primarily because of its unique composition and functions. Unlike typical connective tissues, blood has a **fluid** matrix called plasma as its **ground substance**. The liquid nature of the ground substance allows blood to flow and transport nutrients, gases, hormones, and waste products throughout the body.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile blood does contain cells and some protein fibers such as fibrin (during blood clotting), the primary characteristic distinguishing it as a special connective tissue is its fluid ground substance.\r\n\r\nHydroxyapatite crystals are not a component of blood. These crystals are more related to bone tissue.\r\n\r\nAll connective tissues, including blood, are composed of cells and fibers.","reference":"Anatomy | seer training. Accessed June 22, 2023. https://training.seer.cancer.gov/leukemia/anatomy/","responses":[{"text":"It consists of only fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It has a greater ratio of cells than fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It consists of hydroxyapatite crystals in its matrix","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is composed of cells and fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It has fluid nature of its ground substance","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16148,"text":"Which one of the following is an unencapsulated lymphatic tissue found in the human body?","explanation":"**Peyer patches** are **unencapsulated lymphatic tissue** found in the human body. They are part of the gut-associated lymphoid tissue (GALT) and are specifically located in the submucosa of the small intestine, primarily in the ileum.\r\n\r\nThese patches play a crucial role in the immune response, particularly in monitoring and responding to antigens in the digestive system. They are involved in the production of immunoglobulin A (IgA) and contribute to the defense against pathogens in the gut.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe thymus, lymph nodes, spleen, and tonsils have a capsule.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2013: 276.","responses":[{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tonsils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peyer patches","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymph node","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thymus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16149,"text":"In comparison to primitive hematopoiesis, which of the following is not the feature of definitive hematopoiesis (DH)?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 441.","responses":[{"text":"During definitive hematopoiesis, many types of white blood cells are produced","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Definitive hematopoiesis is permanent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"During definitive hematopoiesis, red blood cells do not have the nuclei","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Definitive hematopoiesis starts in yolk sac","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Definitive hematopoiesis begins in fetal life","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16150,"text":"A biopsy specimen of the thymus from an old man is examined under the microscope and many whorl-like corpuscles are observed. Which of the following statement truly matches the corpuscles mentioned above?","explanation":"**Hassall's corpuscles** are concentrically arranged structures composed of **epithelial reticular cells**, forming a whorl-like pattern. They are typically found in the medulla of the thymus.  The exact function of these structures is not completely understood, but they are believed to play a role in the maturation of T cells.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHassall's corpuscles are not derived from T memory cells. They are composed of epithelial reticular cells.\r\n\r\nHassall's corpuscles have an endodermal origin, not mesodermal.\r\n\r\nHassall's corpuscles are predominantly found in the thymic medulla, not the cortex.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 131.","responses":[{"text":"They are mainly located in the thymic cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They have their embryological origin from mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are derived from T memory cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are frequently seen in thymus of young individuals","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are composed of epithelial reticular cells (type VI)","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16151,"text":"Which of the following proteins stimulates the expansion and multiplication of nearly all types of stem cells?","explanation":"**Interleukin-3** (IL-3) is a cytokine that stimulates the expansion and multiplication of various types of stem cells, making it a key factor in hematopoiesis. IL-3 acts as a pluripotent hematopoietic growth factor, supporting the proliferation and differentiation of **multiple cell lineages**, including erythroid, myeloid, and lymphoid progenitors.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile IL-6 plays a role in hematopoiesis, its effects are primarily focused on T cell and B cell differentiation and activation, not general stem cell expansion.\r\n\r\nGranulocyte colony-stimulating factor (G-CSF) specifically stimulates the production and differentiation of granulocytes i.e., neutrophils, eosinophils, and basophils.\r\n\r\nGranulocyte-macrophage colony-stimulating factor (GM-CSF) stimulates the production and differentiation of both granulocytes and macrophages.\r\n\r\nMacrophage colony-stimulating factor (M-CSF) specifically stimulates the production and differentiation of macrophages.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 441.","responses":[{"text":"Granulocyte colony-stimulating factor (G-CSF)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Granulocyte-macrophage colony-stimulating factor (GM-CSF)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-3 (IL-3)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-6 (IL-6)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophage colony-stimulating factor (M-CSF)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16152,"text":"Which of the following cells does erythropoietin stimulate to enhance RBC synthesis?","explanation":"**Erythropoietin** stimulates the proliferation and differentiation of **colony-forming unit-erythrocytes** (CFU-E), which are committed progenitor cells specifically committed to the erythroid lineage. CFU-E cells further differentiate into reticulocytes and then mature red blood cells (RBCs).\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nErythropoietin does not directly stimulate reticulocytes and basophil erythroblasts. Reticulocytes are the immediate precursors to mature red blood cells and are derived from CFU-E cells.\r\n\r\nProerythroblast is a precursor cell in erythropoiesis, but erythropoietin primarily stimulates CFU-E cells, which are downstream of the proerythroblast stage.\r\n\r\nErythropoeitin acts on more committed progenitor cells in the erythroid lineage, such as CFU-E, rather than pluripotent hematopoietic stem cells.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 441-442.","responses":[{"text":"Pluripotent hematopoietic stem cell (PHSC)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reticulocyles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colony-forming unit-erythrocytes (CFU-E)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophil erythroblasts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proerythroblast","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16153,"text":"Which of the following have MHC-I molecules present on their surfaces?","explanation":"**Major histocompatibility complex class I** (MHC-I) molecules are present on the surfaces of all nucleated cells in the body. MHC-I molecules bind to processed peptide fragments derived from intracellular proteins, specifically **self-antigens**. This prevents most T cells from attacking these cells.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nMHC-II molecules are responsible for presenting processed foreign antigens to helper T cells (CD4+ T cells).\r\n\r\nAntibodies are proteins produced by B cells in response to foreign antigens.\r\n\r\nT cells themselves express MHC molecules (primarily MHC-II), but not MHC-I on their surface.\r\n\r\nCoreceptors, such as CD4 and CD8, are molecules found on the surface of T cells. They are involved in the interaction between T cells and antigen-presenting cells.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2013: 266-267.","responses":[{"text":"Antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coreceptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T cell antigens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Processed foreign antigens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Processed self-antigens","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16154,"text":"A middle-aged obese doctor presents to the emergency room with complaints of significant left-sided chest \"tightness\" and pain that radiates to his left arm and jaw. He was given streptokinase when he was diagnosed with a heart attack four months back. The patient went into shock after receiving a fibrinolytic drug due to a hypersensitivity reaction. Which fibrinolytic agent did the patient receive this time?","explanation":"**Streptokinase** is a fibrinolytic agent that can be used to break down blood clots in patients with a myocardial infarction. However, streptokinase has a **higher antigenicity** than newer fibrinolytic agents and can trigger **hypersensitivity reactions**, leading to adverse effects such as shock.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nUrokinase has a lower antigenicity than streptokinase and carries a lower risk of triggering a hypersensitivity reaction.\r\n\r\nTissue plasminogen activators such as alteplase and retaplase are less likely to cause hypersensitivity reactions.","reference":"Whalen K, Finkel R, Panavelil TA. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 6th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2015: 306-307.","responses":[{"text":"Tissue plasminogen activator","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alteplase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptokinase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Retaplase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urokinase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16198,"text":"Which of the following terms denotes the average weight of hemoglobin in an individual erythrocyte?","explanation":"**Mean corpuscular hemoglobin** (MCH) specifically refers to the average **weight** of **hemoglobin** present in a **single red blood cell**, measured in picograms (pg). It reflects the red blood cell's hemoglobin content and helps assess the cell's ability to carry oxygen.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nMean corpuscular hemoglobin concentration reflects the average concentration of hemoglobin within the packed red blood cell volume, measured in grams per deciliter (g/dL).\r\n\r\nHemoglobin index is a broader term that can encompass various indices calculated from different red blood cell parameters, including MCH.\r\n\r\nMean corpuscular volume (MCV) refers to the average size or volume of an individual red blood cell, measured in femtoliters (fL).\r\n\r\nHematocrit is the percentage of blood volume occupied by red blood cells.","reference":"Red blood cell (Rbc) indices: medlineplus medical test. Accessed June 20, 2023. https://medlineplus.gov/lab-tests/red-blood-cell-rbc-indices/","responses":[{"text":"Mean corpuscular hemoglobin (MCH)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mean corpuscular hemoglobin concentration (MCHC)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mean corpuscular volume (MCV)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin index","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hematocrit","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16199,"text":"A 40-year-old man was recovered after having walked for hours, two days after becoming lost in a sweltering and humid wilderness. His complete blood picture showed increased hematocrit. Which of the following is a likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The man's exposure to a sweltering and humid environment for an extended period is a classic trigger for dehydration. **Dehydration** can lead to a concentration effect, meaning the plasma volume decreases while the number of red blood cells remains relatively constant. This results in an apparent increase in hematocrit (**relative polycythemia**), not a true increase in red blood cell production.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nSecondary polycythemia can occur due to chronic conditions such as hypoxia or kidney disease, which are not mentioned in the case.\r\n\r\nPhysiological polycythemia implies long-term adaptation to high altitudes and does not apply to a transient elevation in hematocrit due to short-term exposure to a hot, humid environment.\r\n\r\nPrimary polycythemia or polycythemia vera is a primary myeloproliferative disorder characterized by an increase in all blood cell types, not just red blood cells. It is not typically associated with short-term exposure to environmental conditions.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 662.\r\n\r\n(2) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020:  447.","responses":[{"text":"Polycythemia vera","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary polycythemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary polycythemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Relative polycythemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Physiological polycythemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16201,"text":"The hematocrit of a person with a tumor-like disease is elevated. What value of hematocrit value would you most likely expect to see?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 447.","responses":[{"text":"More than 70%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"More than 50%","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Less than 30%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10% above normal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"80% above normal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16202,"text":"Which one of the following values corresponds to the percentage of hemoglobin A2 (HbA₂) in a normal adult person?","explanation":"The normal range for the percentage of hemoglobin A₂ (**HbA₂**) in a normal adult person is **2.5 to 3.5%**. HbA₂ is a minor component of adult hemoglobin, and its measurement is significant in the diagnosis of certain hemoglobinopathies, particularly beta-thalassemia.","reference":"Ferrier, Denise R. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2017: 33.","responses":[{"text":"2.5 to 3.5%","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"0.5 to 0.8%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.9 to 1.4%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"4.5 to 5.5%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1.5 to 1.9%","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16204,"text":"A 44-year-old man discovers he is positive for HIV after a blood donation screening. The screening of blood work shows hemoglobin of 10 g/dL, hematocrit 30%, total leukocyte count 4600/mm³, platelet count 15,000/mm³, prothrombin time 12 seconds (INR=1.1), and partial thromboplastin time 23 seconds. Which physical finding is most likely in this patient?","explanation":"**Severe thrombocytopenia** suggests impaired platelet production or increased platelet destruction. **Petechiae** are small, pinpoint, red or purple spots on the skin caused by minor bleeding from broken capillaries. They are a common manifestation of thrombocytopenia.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nVisceral hematomas are larger collections of blood in internal organs and are not typically associated with thrombocytopenia alone.\r\n\r\nWhile an increased risk of deep venous thrombosis (DVT) is associated with HIV infection, it typically presents with specific symptoms such as leg pain and swelling, which are not mentioned in this case.\r\n\r\nSubungual hemorrhage refers to the accumulation under the nails. It is typically associated with trauma, not thrombocytopenia.\r\n\r\nHemarthrosis (bleeding into joints) is more likely to occur in patients with a deficiency or dysfunction of clotting factors rather than platelets.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 485.","responses":[{"text":"Subungual hemorrhage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep venous thrombosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Petechiae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemarthrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Visceral hematoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16206,"text":"A 44-year-old man is treated with high doses of rabbit anti-thymocyte globulin for bone marrow failure. He develops fever, lymphadenopathy, arthralgias, and erythema of the hands and feet arise ten days later. Which of the following is the most probable explanation for these signs and symptoms?","explanation":"This patient has been treated with high doses of **rabbit anti-thymocyte globulin**, which is a polyclonal **antibody preparation** derived from rabbits targeting and depleting T lymphocytes. However, it can also bind to other immune cells and components, potentially forming immune complexes with circulating antigens. The subsequent development of fever, lymphadenopathy, arthralgias, and erythema points toward an **immune complex hypersensitivity reaction**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile natural killer cells play a role in immune responses, the secretion of cytokines alone is less likely to cause such widespread inflammatory symptoms.\r\n\r\nEosinophil degranulation is often associated with allergic reactions and parasitic infections.\r\n\r\nWidespread apoptosis of B lymphocytes would result in immunosuppression and increased susceptibility to infection.\r\n\r\nRATG aims to deplete T lymphocytes, not activate them. Therefore, widespread T-cell activation is unlikely in this case.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 211.","responses":[{"text":"Polyclonal T-lymphocyte activation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytokine secretion by natural killer cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophil degranulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Immune complex deposition in tissues","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Widespread apoptosis of B lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16208,"text":"A 20-year-old lady visits the doctor, after five years of significant menstrual bleeding. She complains of easy bruising and states that bleeding from a tiny finger cut lasts longer than normal. Lab results show a hemoglobin of 10.5g/dL, and a platelet count of 275,000/mm^3, with normal platelet aggregation. Prothrombin time is 10.5 seconds (INR = 1.0) and аctivated partial thromboplastin time is 28 sec. Pap smear shows no abnormalities. Which of the following hematologic disorders is the most likely cause of this patient's menorrhagia?","explanation":"The most likely cause of the patient's **menorrhagia** in this case is **Von Willebrand disease** (VWD), which is marked by significant menstrual bleeding, easy bruising, and prolonged bleeding from a minor cut.\r\n\r\nThe activated partial thromboplastin time (**aPTT**) is **prolonged**, indicating a defect in the intrinsic pathway of coagulation, which is a characteristic feature of VWD while platelet count and platelet aggregation are normal.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAfibrinogenemia is characterized by the absence of fibrinogen, leading to severe bleeding. However, it typically presents with a prolonged prothrombin time (PT), which is normal in this case.\r\n\r\nHemophilia A is a deficiency of factor VIII, and it presents with prolonged aPTT. However, it is more commonly associated with joint and soft tissue bleeding rather than menorrhagia.\r\n\r\nIntravascular coagulation is a condition associated with both bleeding and clotting. The laboratory findings in DIC would typically show consumption of clotting factors, leading to the prolongation of both PT and aPTT.\r\n\r\n Vitamin K deficiency would lead to prolonged PT and raised platelet count.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 668.","responses":[{"text":"Von Willebrand disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin K deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Afibrinogenemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravascular coagulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia A","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16210,"text":"Which of the following features characterizes fetal hemoglobin compared to adult hemoglobin?","explanation":"**Fetal hemoglobin** (HbF) differs from adult hemoglobin (HbA) in that it possesses **more affinity for oxygen**. This enhanced affinity allows fetal hemoglobin to extract oxygen more efficiently from the maternal circulation, where oxygen pressure is lower than in the fetal circulation.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nBoth fetal and adult hemoglobins have four pyrrole rings per heme group.\r\n\r\nFetal hemoglobin has two alpha chains and two gamma chains (α2γ2), while adult hemoglobin has two alpha chains and two beta chains (α2β2). There is no delta polypeptide chain in fetal hemoglobin.\r\n\r\nFetal hemoglobin exhibits a higher oxygen affinity, leading to increased oxygen content at a given partial pressure of oxygen compared to adult hemoglobin.\r\n\r\nAlthough HbF releases oxygen slightly less readily than HbA, it still readily supplies tissues with oxygen when needed.","reference":"Murray RK, Victor WR, Bender D, Kathleen MB, Weil PA, Kennelly PJ. Harper’s Illustrated Biochemistry. 28th ed. McGraw-Hill Professional; 2009: 45.","responses":[{"text":"It has delta polypeptide chain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It contains five pyrrole rings","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It unloads oxygen to tissues with difficulty","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It possesses more affinity for oxygen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It shows lesser oxygen content at a given partial pressure of oxygen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16211,"text":"After the breakdown of red blood cells, which of the following proteins binds hemoglobin to be cleared by liver macrophages?","explanation":"After **hemolysis**, hemoglobin is released into the bloodstream. To prevent the loss of hemoglobin through renal filtration, hemoglobin is bound by a protein called haptoglobin. The **haptoglobin-hemoglobin complex** is then recognized by liver **macrophages**, facilitating its clearance from the bloodstream.\r\n\r\nThe interaction between haptoglobin and hemoglobin serves to prevent the potentially toxic effects of oxidation of free hemoglobin in circulation.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nBilirubin is a product of heme breakdown that is produced after hemoglobin is broken down by macrophages in the spleen.\r\n\r\nHemopexin is a protein that binds free heme, not hemoglobin. It plays a role in transporting heme to the liver.\r\n\r\nHepcidin is a peptide hormone that regulates iron homeostasis. It does not directly bind to hemoglobin.\r\n\r\nHemin is a form of heme, the iron-containing component of hemoglobin.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 475.","responses":[{"text":"Hemopexin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepcidin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haptoglobin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bilirubin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16212,"text":"A 5-year-old child was brought to a clinic with complaints of high-grade fever, pain in the throat, and difficulty in swallowing. Examination and a blood test confirmed the diagnosis of acute bacterial infection of the tonsils. Which of the following cells would be increased in blood in this condition?","explanation":"**Neutrophils** are the primary responders to bacterial infections and play a crucial role in the innate immune response.\r\n\r\nDuring an **acute bacterial infection** such as bacterial tonsillitis, the body mobilizes neutrophils to the site of infection to **phagocytose** and eliminate the invading bacteria. The increased presence of neutrophils in the blood, known as **neutrophilia**, is a characteristic response to bacterial infections.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nBasophils are primarily involved in allergic reactions and parasitic infections.\r\n\r\nEosinophils are involved in allergic reactions and defense against parasitic infections.\r\n\r\nWhile lymphocytes play a crucial role in the adaptive immune response, they are not the first-line responders to acute bacterial infections.\r\n\r\nMast cells are involved in allergic reactions and inflammatory responses. They are not the primary cells that are typically increased in response to acute bacterial infections.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 455.","responses":[{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mast cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16213,"text":"A 68-year-old male with carcinoma of the lung was given subcutaneous heparin to prevent any intravascular coagulation. The activity of this anticoagulant is increased when it combines with a protein. Which one of the following proteins shows this effect?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 484.","responses":[{"text":"Protein C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombomodulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Von Willebrand factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antithrombin III","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Protein S","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16214,"text":"A young woman presents to the outpatient department with complaints of being exhausted and short of breath when she tries to do anything. She has a respiratory rate of 18 breaths per minute and is quite pale. Hemoglobin is 10 g/dL according to the lab results. What is the approximate amount of oxygen that is transported by each one hundred milliliters of her blood?","explanation":"The maximum amount of oxygen **1 g of hemoglobin** is capable of binding to is **1.34 ml of oxygen**.\r\n\r\nThe approximate amount of oxygen that is transported by each one hundred milliliters of blood can be estimated using the formula:\r\n\r\n**Oxygen content = (hemoglobin × 1.34 × oxygen saturation) + 0.0031 × PaO₂**\r\n\r\nIn normal conditions, hemoglobin is about 98-99% saturated with oxygen i.e., oxygen saturation ≈ 0.98-0.99.\r\n\r\nOxygen content = (10 × 1.34 × 0.98) + 0.0031 × PaO2\r\n​\r\nFor simplification, assuming a typical PaO₂, the main contributors to oxygen content are hemoglobin concentration and oxygen saturation.\r\n\r\nOxygen content = (10 × 1.34 × 0.98)\r\n\r\nSo, the **approximate amount of oxygen** transported by **100 ml of her blood** is **≈ 13 mL**.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 524.","responses":[{"text":"15 mL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20 mL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10 mL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"8 mL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"13 mL","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16215,"text":"A 65-year-old woman arrives at the orthopedic department with joint pain. Her doctor diagnoses her with osteoarthritis and osteoporosis. She is prescribed NSAIDs, calcium, and vitamin D. She returns after six months on the same medication, pale and short of breath. Her MCV is 73 fL and her hemoglobin was 9 g/dL. What could be the cause of low hemoglobin?","explanation":"Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) that are commonly prescribed for osteoarthritis, can cause gastrointestinal bleeding, leading to **iron deficiency** and ultimately **anemia**. The **low mean corpuscular volume** (MCV) and **hemoglobin** levels further confirm this suspicion.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile liver disease can cause various blood abnormalities, the clinical presentation and the context of the patient's joint issues make iron deficiency more likely.\r\n\r\nThalassemia is a genetic disorder typically diagnosed in childhood or early adulthood, making it less likely in this case, considering the patient's age at the time of onset of symptoms.\r\n\r\nSickle cell anemia is associated with normal levels of hemoglobin and a normal MCV.\r\n\r\nAplastic anemia involves bone marrow suppression, leading to a decrease in all blood cell lines, not just red blood cells.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 655, 658.","responses":[{"text":"Thalassemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle cell anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16216,"text":"A 24-year-old Indian male arrives at the emergency room with severe chest and back pain that started three hours earlier while he was ascending a mountain and was short of breath. He states that he experienced identical symptoms several years earlier. Lab tests show that hemoglobin is 10 g/dL, total leukocyte count is 12,000/mm3, MCV is 87 fL, and reticulocytes are 25%. What could be his diagnosis?","explanation":"Sickle cell anemia is a genetic disorder characterized by the presence of abnormal hemoglobin (HbS), which leads to the formation of sickle-shaped red blood cells. These cells can cause a **vaso-occlusive crisis**, leading to **severe pain** and organ damage, particularly during physical stress or dehydration.\r\n\r\nIn this case, as the patient climbs the mountain, the reduced oxygen levels and physical exertion likely triggered the widespread sickling of red blood cells. Sickle cells are typically normocytic with a normal mean corpuscular volume (MCV).\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nIron deficiency anemia and thalassemia are typically associated with microcytic red blood cells with a low MCV.\r\n\r\nLiver disease may cause various blood abnormalities, but the specific clinical presentation and lab findings in this case are more indicative of sickle cell anemia.\r\n\r\nAplastic anemia typically presents with pancytopenia.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 641.","responses":[{"text":"Liver disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thalassemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle cell anemia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16217,"text":"A manufacturing company worker who looks sick, feverish, and tired, complains of bleeding from the nose and gums. The laboratory findings show that the patient has low levels of hemoglobin, white blood cells, and platelets, as well as a low reticulocyte count and a mean corpuscular volume of 88 fL. What could be the potential diagnosis?","explanation":"Bleeding from the nose and gums, along with low levels of hemoglobin, white blood cells, and platelets, suggests the possibility of aplastic anemia.\r\n\r\n**Aplastic anemia** typically results from damage to the bone marrow. The bone marrow fails to produce an adequate number of blood cells, leading to pancytopenia. **Low levels of platelets** can lead to bleeding from the nose and gums. The **low reticulocyte count** and the **normal mean corpuscular volume** of 88 fL further support the diagnosis.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n Liver disease can lead to various blood abnormalities, but it is not the primary cause of pancytopenia.\r\n\r\nThalassemia and iron deficiency anemia are associated with microcytic red blood cells with a low MCV (less than 80 fL).\r\n\r\nSickle cell anemia is not typically associated with low levels of white blood cells and platelets.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 659.","responses":[{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thalassemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle cell anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16218,"text":"A 27-year-old Ethiopian male presents to the outpatient department with breathlessness. He has a high heart rate and pale oral mucosa and conjunctiva. His initial blood tests showed 7.8 g/dL hemoglobin and 65 fL MCV. The doctor advises iron studies, which are normal. What could be the diagnosis?","explanation":"Breathlessness and pallor of the oral mucosa and conjunctiva, along with low hemoglobin (7.8 g/dL) are indicative of anemia.\r\n\r\n**Thalassemia** is a genetic disorder characterized by decreased production of hemoglobin, leading to microcytic, hypochromic red blood cells. Iron studies in patients with thalassemia are typically normal.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAplastic anemia involves a reduction in the number of all types of blood cells (red cells, white cells, and platelets) due to bone marrow failure. \r\n\r\nNormal iron studies make liver disease and iron deficiency anemia less likely in this case.\r\n\r\nSickle cell anemia is characterized by the presence of abnormal hemoglobin (HbS), leading to crescent-shaped red blood cells. These cells are typically normocytic, not microcytic.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 644-646.","responses":[{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thalassemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle cell anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16219,"text":"A 24-year-old media sciences student presents with exhaustion, nausea, and vomiting for one week. She also has a low-grade fever and visited the outpatient department after observing yellow skin and sclera. Abdominal examination reveals right upper abdominal discomfort. Her liver tests are abnormal. She is diagnosed with hepatitis A after testing. Which immunity will she build from her acute viral infection?","explanation":"**Natural active immunity** comes into play when an individual is exposed to a pathogen (in this case, the hepatitis A virus). The immune system produces antibodies and memory cells specific to the virus, protecting against future infections. This type of immunity is a result of the natural course of infection.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nNatural passive immunity involves the transfer of pre-formed antibodies from a mother to her infant (via breast milk or placenta).\r\n\r\nInnate immunity is the first line of defense against infections and is not specific to a particular pathogen. It includes physical barriers, white blood cells, and chemical mediators.\r\n\r\nArtificial passive immunity involves the administration of pre-formed antibodies obtained from an external source, such as immune serum globulin.\r\n\r\nArtificial active immunity is induced by vaccination, where the individual is exposed to an antigen to stimulate an immune response.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 459.","responses":[{"text":"Innate immunity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Natural passive immunity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Artificial passive immunity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Natural active immunity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Artificial active immunity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16220,"text":"A young man presented to the outpatient department with complaints of fever for 5 days and body aches. He has stable blood pressure, 103° C temperature, 110 beats/min pulse, and 20 breaths/min respiration. His total leukocyte count was 2500/μL. Which reflects his condition best?","explanation":"**Leukopenia** refers to a decreased number of white blood cells (leukocytes) in the blood.\r\n\r\nA **low leukocyte count**, along with symptoms of fever and body aches, is suggestive of a viral infection. Viral infections can transiently decrease the number of circulating white blood cells, leading to leukopenia.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nLeukoplakia refers to white patches on the mucous membranes, particularly in the mouth.\r\n\r\nLeukocytosis refers to an elevated white blood cell count.\r\n\r\nLeukemia is a malignant disorder characterized by uncontrolled proliferation of white blood cells.\r\n\r\n A leukemoid reaction is an exaggerated response of the bone marrow to various stressors, often leading to a marked increase in white blood cell count.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 457.","responses":[{"text":"Leukemoid reaction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukopenia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukoplakia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16232,"text":"Elevated concentration of lactate in the plasma is associated with which of the following?","explanation":"During intense physical activity, the energy demand exceeds the supply, leading to **anaerobic metabolism**. In the absence of sufficient oxygen, pyruvate generated from glycolysis is converted into lactate. **Increased lactate** levels are a result of the muscles working anaerobically, producing lactate as a byproduct. This is known as lactic acidosis, and it contributes to **muscle fatigue** and soreness experienced after vigorous physical activity.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nElevated lactate levels are not directly associated with iron deficiency anemia. Iron deficiency anemia is characterized by a decrease in the oxygen-carrying capacity of hemoglobin.\r\n\r\nWhile elevated lactate levels can occur in severe cases of myocardial infarction, exercise-induced muscle fatigue is a more specific association in this context.\r\n\r\nVitamin D deficiency is associated with calcium metabolism and bone health.\r\n\r\nDehydration can lead to an increased concentration of various blood solutes, but it is not a direct cause of elevated lactate levels.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 260, 850.","responses":[{"text":"Vitamin D deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocardial infarction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Exercise-induced muscle fatigue","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dehydration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16233,"text":"When interpreting an iron profile, which of the following parameters is the most reliable indicator of iron deficiency?","explanation":"The most reliable indicator of **iron deficiency** is the measurement of ferritin levels. Ferritin is an intracellular protein that stores iron and releases it in a controlled fashion. Elevated **ferritin levels** in the blood usually indicate increased iron stores, while low levels suggest iron deficiency.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nSerum hepcidin levels can be influenced by various factors, and its direct measurement is not routinely used for the diagnosis of iron deficiency.\r\n\r\nTotal iron-binding capacity (TIBC) measures the capacity of transferrin to bind iron. While TIBC can provide information about iron status, it is not as specific as ferritin in indicating iron deficiency.\r\n\r\nSerum iron levels alone may not be a reliable indicator of iron deficiency, as they can vary throughout the day and are influenced by factors other than iron status.\r\n\r\n: Transferrin saturation is the ratio of serum iron to TIBC and provides an estimate of how much transferrin is saturated with iron. While it can be informative, it is not as specific as ferritin in indicating iron deficiency.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 657.","responses":[{"text":"Serum hepcidin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferritin levels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum iron levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Total iron-binding capacity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transferrin saturation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16235,"text":"Which of the following is the first bile pigment produced in the catabolism of heme molecule?","explanation":"In the catabolism of the heme molecule, the initial step involves the action of **heme oxygenase**, which converts heme into **biliverdin**. Biliverdin is a green-colored pigment and represents the first stage in the breakdown of heme. This process is crucial for the removal of heme from hemoglobin and other heme-containing molecules.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nLithocholic acid is a secondary bile acid formed through the modification of primary bile acids.\r\n\r\nCholic acid and deoxycholic acid are primary bile acids synthesized from cholesterol and are unrelated to the initial steps of heme catabolism.\r\n\r\nBilirubin is the final product of heme catabolism.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 874.","responses":[{"text":"Cholic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deoxycholic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biliverdin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lithocholic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bilirubin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16236,"text":"What is the net yield of ATP molecules produced by the glycolysis of one glucose molecule in red blood cells?","explanation":"During **glycolysis**, two ATP molecules are consumed in the early steps (investment phase) to activate glucose. However, four ATP molecules are produced in the later steps (payoff phase), resulting in a **net gain of 2 ATP molecules**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAfter glycolysis, pyruvate enters the Krebs cycle and produces additional ATP, leading to a total yield of around 36 ATP molecules per glucose molecule. However, the Krebs cycle does not occur in the red blood cells.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 846.","responses":[{"text":"36 ATP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0 ATP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"6 ATP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 ATP","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"1 ATP","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16238,"text":"Which form of vitamin K is required for the activation of clotting factors?","explanation":"The form of vitamin K required for the **activation of clotting factors** is hydroquinone. **Hydroquinone** is the active form of vitamin K in the vitamin K-dependent carboxylation of clotting factors II (prothrombin), VII, IX, and X in the liver. These clotting factors require carboxylation for their functional activity in the coagulation cascade.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nMenadione is a synthetic form of vitamin K that needs to be converted to the active hydroquinone form in the body.\r\n\r\nPhylloquinone, also known as vitamin K1, is the natural form of vitamin K found in green leafy vegetables. It is converted to hydroquinone in the body for its biological activities.\r\n\r\nMenaquinone, also known as vitamin K2, is a form of vitamin K produced by bacteria in the intestines. Like phylloquinone, it is converted to hydroquinone for its biological activity.\r\n\r\nDimenadione is a synthetic compound related to vitamin K, but it is not a naturally occurring form and is not used for biological activities in the same way as hydroquinone.","reference":"Simes DC, Viegas CSB, Araújo N, Marreiros C. Vitamin k as a diet supplement with impact in human health: current evidence in age-related diseases. Nutrients. 2020;12(1):138. doi:10.3390/nu12010138","responses":[{"text":"Menaquinone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Menadione","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dimenadione","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phylloquinone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydroquinone","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16241,"text":"The plasma proteins electrophoresis shows two major protein electrophoretic bands, one for albumin and the other for globulin. Globulin further gives different fractions. These are α1 globulins, α2 globulin, β1 globulin, β2 globulin, and γ globulins. Which of the following is the protein present in the γ globulin fraction?","explanation":"Plasma protein electrophoresis refers to the separation of proteins is based on their electrical charge and size. **Immunoglobulins** (Ig) migrate to the **γ globulin fraction**. This fraction consists mainly of antibodies, IgA, IgE, IgG, IgM, IgD, and IgE.\r\n\r\nImmunoglobulins (Ig), also known as antibodies, are proteins produced by plasma cells and are an essential component of the immune system. They are Y-shaped protein molecules responsible for the body's humoral immune response. They bind to specific pathogens or foreign antigens, marking them for destruction by phagocytic cells or activating complement pathways.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHaptoglobin belongs to the α1 globulin fraction and binds free hemoglobin in the bloodstream, preventing iron loss and promoting its recycling.\r\n\r\nCeruloplasmin is a copper-transporting protein that is also found in the α1 globulin fraction.\r\n\r\nAcid glycoprotein belongs to the β1 globulin fraction.\r\n\r\nTransthyretin is responsible for transporting thyroid hormones and retinol. It resides in the prealbumin fraction, just before the α1 globulin fraction.","reference":"Fahey JL. Antibodies and immunoglobulins: i. Structure and function. JAMA. Published October 4, 1965. Accessed December 20, 2023. https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/article-abstract/656674","responses":[{"text":"Acid glycoprotein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Immunoglobulins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Haptoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ceruloplasmin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transthyretin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16242,"text":"What is the most characteristic feature of granulation tissue?","explanation":"**Granulation tissue** is repair tissue that forms during the healing process of a wound or injury. It is marked by angiogenesis and fibroplasia.\r\n\r\nAngiogenesis refers to the formation of new blood vessels, particularly **capillaries**, which contribute to its red, granular appearance. Fibroplasia, on the other, refers to the **proliferation of fibroblasts**, which are involved in the synthesis of collagen fibers, promoting tissue repair and scar formation.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile there might be some initial exudate in the early stages of inflammation, granulation tissue is associated with the proliferative and reparative phases of wound healing.\r\n\r\nMonocytes and fibroblasts are involved in the formation and maturation of granulation tissue, but the growth of fibroblasts is a more specific and characteristic feature.\r\n\r\nGranulation tissue and granulomas are distinct entities. Granulation tissue is part of the normal wound healing process, while granuloma is a specific type of chronic inflammatory response characterized by the aggregation of immune cells.\r\n\r\nWhile there may be some presence of neutrophils and macrophages in the early inflammatory phase, the characteristic feature of granulation tissue is the later growth of fibroblasts and new capillaries during the reparative phase.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 106.","responses":[{"text":"Presence of monocytes and fibroblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Resemblance to granuloma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Presence of neutrophils and macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Growth of fibroblasts and new capillaries","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Presence of exudate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16243,"text":"A 41-year-old man comes into the medical outpatient department with complaints of weight loss, nausea, and vomiting for 5 months. He works at a factory that produces plastic pipes. On physical examination, he has tenderness to palpation in the right upper quadrant of the abdomen with hepatomegaly. An abdominal CT scan shows a 12 cm mass in the right lobe of the liver. A liver biopsy is performed, and a microscopic examination shows an angiosarcoma. The patient has most likely been exposed to which of the following agents?","explanation":"The patient's occupation as a factory worker in a facility producing **plastic pipes** is suggestive of exposure to **vinyl chloride**.\r\n\r\nVinyl chloride is a chemical used in the production of polyvinyl chloride (PVC), a common material in the plastics industry. It is a well-documented risk factor for **angiosarcoma of the liver**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAngiosarcoma is not a typical manifestation of arsenic exposure.\r\n\r\nBeryllium is mainly linked to lung cancer and chronic beryllium disease.\r\n\r\nBenzene exposure can increase the risk of leukemia.\r\n\r\nAsbestos primarily affects the pleural lining.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 280.","responses":[{"text":"Benzene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vinyl chloride","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Beryllium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asbestos","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arsenic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16244,"text":"A 25-year-old male patient visited the outpatient department with complaints of shortness of breath at rest. His chest is normal on auscultation and there are no visible signs of lung disease on X-ray. He has low hemoglobin and an MCV of 105 fL based on his blood tests. Multisegmented neutrophils are not seen on blood smear. What could be the cause of his anemia?","explanation":"The clinical presentation of shortness of breath at rest, low hemoglobin, and slightly raised mean corpuscular volume (MCV) with no multisegmented neutrophils on blood smear suggests a type of **anemia** associated with **ineffective erythropoiesis**. In this case, the cause of anemia is likely related to an **underlying liver disease**.\r\n\r\nLiver disease, especially in severe cases, can suppress the bone marrow's ability to produce red blood cells. This condition can be further exacerbated by the impaired absorption of vitamin B9 and B12 associated with chronic liver diseases.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAplastic anemia is characterized by a decrease in the number of all types of blood cells (red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets). The described blood smear with macrocytes (MCV greater than 100 fL) findings do not fit the characteristics of aplastic anemia.\r\n\r\nThe high MCV in this case makes iron deficiency and thalassemia less likely, which are typically associated with microcytes (MCV less than 80 fL).\r\n\r\nSickle cell anemia is associated with cresent-shaped red blood cells, which are not seen in this case.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 661.","responses":[{"text":"Liver disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle cell anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thalassemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16245,"text":"An 18-year-old male comes to the outpatient department with a palpable mass on the right side of his neck for 6 months. On physical examination, there is a 2 cm, firm, non-tender nodule involving the right lobe of the thyroid gland. Biopsy specimens of the nodule showed features consistent with carcinoma of the thyroid. No positive family history was found. Which of the following is relevant in the woman's past medical history?","explanation":"Exposure to ionizing radiation, especially during **childhood**, is a well-established risk factor for the development of thyroid carcinoma. In individuals who receive **radiation therapy** to the head and neck region, the thyroid gland is particularly susceptible to the effects of radiation. The latency period between radiation exposure and the development of **thyroid cancer** can be several years.\r\n\r\nOther risk factors for thyroid cancer include family history and genetic predisposition.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nArsenic exposure, alcohol, blunt trauma, and ataxia telangiectasia are not direct risk factors for thyroid carcinoma.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 432.","responses":[{"text":"Chronic alcoholism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Exposure to arsenic compounds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blunt trauma from a fall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radiation therapy in childhood","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ataxia telangiectasia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16246,"text":"A 52-year-old man noted a darkly pigmented \"mole\" on the back of his hand. During the past month, the lesion has gradually enlarged and bled spontaneously. On examination, there is a slightly raised, darkly pigmented, 1.2 cm lesion on the dorsum of the right hand. The lesion is completely excised. Microscopically, malignant melanoma is diagnosed. Which of the following factors is associated with the greatest risk for the development of this neoplasm?","explanation":"Excessive **exposure to UV radiation**, whether from sunlight or artificial sources like tanning beds, can lead to DNA damage in skin cells, increasing the risk of malignant transformation. Individuals with a history of sunburns, outdoor occupations, or excessive sun exposure, especially in fair-skinned individuals, have an increased risk of developing **malignant melanoma**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nChemotherapy is not a known risk factor for the development of malignant melanoma.\r\n\r\nAsbestos exposure is primarily associated with mesothelioma.\r\n\r\nLatex allergy is not associated with an increased risk of malignant melanoma.\r\n\r\nSmoking is not a major risk factor for malignant melanoma. However, it is a well-established risk factor for various other cancers, particularly those related to the respiratory system.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 323.","responses":[{"text":"Smoking tobacco","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultraviolet radiation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Asbestos exposure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemotherapy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Allergy to latex","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16247,"text":"A 58-year-old woman experienced an increased feeling of fullness in the neck for the past 3 months and noted a 3 kg weight loss during that time. On physical examination, there is a firm, fixed mass in a 3 × 5 cm area on the right side of the neck. A biopsy of the mass is performed. All areas of the tumor have similar morphology. Which of the following terms best describes this neoplasm?","explanation":"**Anaplastic carcinoma** refers to a **highly malignant** and undifferentiated tumor with **poor cellular differentiation**. It often represents the dedifferentiation of other thyroid cancers, particularly papillary or follicular carcinomas. Anaplastic carcinomas are associated with rapid growth, local invasion, and a poor prognosis.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nSquamous cell carcinoma is not a common histological type of thyroid cancer. It is more associated with the epithelial lining of organs and tends to exhibit some degree of differentiation.\r\n\r\nWell-differentiated adenocarcinoma is not in line with the lack of cell differentiation seen in this case.\r\n\r\nLeiomyoma is a benign tumor that typically arises from smooth muscle cells in the uterus or gastrointestinal tract.\r\n\r\nAdenomas are benign tumors that are usually well-differentiated.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1090.","responses":[{"text":"Adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leiomyoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Well-differentiated adenocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anaplastic carcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16249,"text":"Malignant neoplasms can be categorized as carcinomas and sarcomas. Which of the following statements describes carcinoma?","explanation":"**Carcinomas** are malignant neoplasms that arise from the **epithelium**. The epithelium is a tissue that covers the body surfaces, both external and internal, and forms glands. Carcinomas can originate from various types of epithelial cells, including those lining the skin and internal organs.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile many carcinomas do arise from tissues derived from the ectoderm, not all do. For example, carcinomas of the digestive system arise from endodermal tissues.\r\n\r\nSarcomas, not carcinomas, arise from mesenchymal tissues.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 269.","responses":[{"text":"Arising exclusively from the cells of mesodermal origin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arising from sheets of solid mesenchyme","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arising exclusively from the epithelium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Arising exclusively from the cells of ectodermal origin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arising exclusively from the cells of endodermal origin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16250,"text":"A 26-year-old woman has a lump in her left breast. On physical examination, the physician finds an irregular, firm, 2 cm mass in the upper inner quadrant of the breast. A fine-needle aspirate of the mass shows carcinoma. The patient's 30-year-old sister was recently diagnosed with ovarian cancer, and 3 years ago her maternal aunt was diagnosed with ductal carcinoma of the breast and had a mastectomy. Which of the following genes is most likely to have undergone mutation to produce these findings","explanation":"The **early onset** of breast carcinoma in a young woman with a **family history** of both breast and ovarian cancer raises suspicion of an inherited genetic mutation, particularly in a BRCA gene.\r\n\r\n**BRCA1** is a tumor suppressor gene involved in DNA repair. Mutations in BRCA1 are associated with an increased risk of **breast** and **ovarian cancers**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nMutations in epidermal growth factor (EGF) genes are not known to be associated with a hereditary predisposition to breast cancer.\r\n\r\nMutations in ERBB2 are more common in HER2-positive breast cancers, known for their overexpression of the HER2 protein. No information about HER2 status is provided in the case.\r\n\r\nBCL2 (anti-apoptosis gene) is involved in programmed cell death. Overexpression of BCL2 can be associated with some breast cancers, but mutations are rare.\r\n\r\nHSTI (fibroblast growth factor gene) is a fibroblast growth factor gene. Mutations in HSTI are mainly related to certain types of leukemia and are not commonly involved in breast cancer.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 314.","responses":[{"text":"ERBB2 (growth factor receptor gene)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"BCL2 (anti-apoptosis gene)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"BRCA1 (DNA repair gene)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"HSTI (fibroblast growth factor gene)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"EGF (epidermal growth factor gene)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16258,"text":"A first-year medical student develops pneumonia and is in the hospital for a week. Two weeks after hospital discharge, he develops a fever and begins coughing up thick, whitish, foul-smelling sputum. Computed tomography (CT) scan chest shows a localized collection of thick fluid in the lung. How would you best describe the outcome of acute inflammation in this patient?","explanation":"Recurrence of fever and cough with foul-smelling sputum is indicative of an ongoing infection and incomplete resolution of the patient's pneumonia. Persistent infection can lead to the formation of an **abscess**, which is a localized collection of **thick, purulent fluid** composed of dead cells, tissue debris, and bacteria. Abscess formation is often accompanied by a fever, as seen in this case.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nFibrosis refers to the formation of scar tissue, often as a result of chronic inflammation.\r\n\r\nGranulomas are organized collections of immune cells, often seen in chronic inflammatory conditions such as tuberculosis or fungal infections.\r\n\r\nUlcers typically involve the loss of tissue and can occur in chronic inflammatory conditions or as a result of specific pathological processes.\r\n\r\nResolution refers to the complete restoration of tissue structure and function after an inflammatory response.","reference":"Kuhajda I, Zarogoulidis K, Tsirgogianni K, et al. Lung abscess-etiology, diagnostic and treatment options. Annals of Translational Medicine. Published August 2015. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26366400/","responses":[{"text":"Resolution","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abscess formation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Granuloma formation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcer formation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16259,"text":"What term best describes the type of inflammation in a 4-year-old child with redness and blister formation on the hands after accidental contact with boiling water?","explanation":"**Serous inflammation** involves the exudation of a watery, protein-rich fluid. In this case, the redness and blister formation are indicative of an acute inflammatory response to the **thermal injury**. The **blister fluid** is typically a serous exudate, containing plasma proteins and sometimes inflammatory cells.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nGranulomatous inflammation involves the formation of granulomas, which are not typical in the acute response to thermal injury.\r\n\r\nUlcerative inflammation is associated with the loss of tissue, leading to ulcer formation.\r\n\r\nSuppurative inflammation involves the formation of pus, which is a fluid rich in neutrophils. While blister fluid can contain inflammatory cells, the term \"suppurative\" specifically implies a more purulent exudate.\r\n\r\nFibrinous inflammation involves the deposition of fibrin.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 93.","responses":[{"text":"Serous","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Suppurative","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Granulomatous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16260,"text":"Which statement best describes autosomal dominant disorders?","explanation":"Autosomal disorders are characterized by reduced penetrance and variable expressivity.\r\n\r\n**Reduced penetrance** signifies that not all individuals inheriting the mutant allele will express the phenotype. Some individuals may carry the dominant allele but do not show signs or symptoms of the disorder.\r\n\r\n**Variable expressivity** means that individuals with the same genotype may exhibit a range of phenotypic expressions. The severity of symptoms can vary even among individuals carrying the same dominant allele.\r\n\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe age of onset for autosomal dominant disorders can vary. It may occur early in life, but it can also manifest later.\r\n\r\nIn autosomal dominant inheritance, a single copy of the mutant allele is sufficient to express the phenotype and cause the disorder. They do not require a homozygous state for the expression of the phenotype.\r\n\r\nAutosomal dominant disorders often result from a gain-of-function mutation, where the mutant allele produces a protein with altered function, rather than a loss of function.\r\n\r\nWhile new mutations can be clinically detected, the statement does not specifically characterize autosomal dominant disorders. The detectability of new mutations depends on various factors.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 144.","responses":[{"text":"Protein shows loss of function","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"New mutations detected early clinically","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced penetrance and variable expressivity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Onset usually early in life","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Disease in homozygous state","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16261,"text":"An affected male does not transmit the disorder to his sons, but all daughters are carriers. Which pattern of inheritance corresponds to the above statement?","explanation":"The pattern described, where an affected male does not transmit the disorder to his sons but all daughters are carriers, is indicative of **X-linked recessive inheritance**.\r\n\r\nIn X-linked recessive inheritance:\r\n\r\n- Affected males inherit the mutant gene from their carrier mothers.\r\n- Sons of affected males inherit the Y chromosome and not the X chromosome carrying the mutant gene, so they do not express the disorder.\r\n- Daughters of affected males inherit one affected X chromosome, making them carriers, as they also receive an unaffected X chromosome from the mother\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nIf a disorder is autosomal dominant, an affected individual has a 50% chance of passing the disorder to each offspring, regardless of gender.\r\n\r\nIn autosomal recessive disorders, both parents must be carriers for a child to be affected.\r\n\r\nSex chromosome abnormality is not a specific inheritance pattern.\r\n\r\nIn X-linked dominant inheritance, an affected male would pass the disorder to all his daughters and sons.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 146.","responses":[{"text":"X-linked recessive","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Autosomal dominant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sex chromosome abnormality","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X-linked dominant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autosomal recessive","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16262,"text":"Which cell type is most likely to be increased in a first year medical student experiencing excessive sneezing and watering of the eyes every year during spring and summer?","explanation":"**Excessive sneezing** and **watering of the eyes**, especially during specific seasons like spring and summer, are indicative of **allergic rhinitis**, commonly known as hay fever.\r\n\r\n**Eosinophils** play a crucial role in allergic reactions. Exposure to allergens triggers the release of inflammatory mediators, leading to the recruitment of eosinophils to the affected tissues.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nMonocytes are white blood cells that differentiate into macrophages. They are involved in phagocytosis.\r\n\r\n Neutrophils are the most abundant type of white blood cells and play a key role in the innate immune response, particularly in bacterial infections\r\n\r\nBasophils release histamine and other mediators during allergic reactions, but they are less numerous than eosinophils. Eosinophils are more prominently involved in allergic responses.\r\n\r\n Lymphocytes are a diverse group of white blood cells, including T cells, B cells, and natural killer cells. These cells play a role in adaptive immunity","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 207, 683.","responses":[{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophils","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Monocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16263,"text":"A 34-year-old man complains of epigastric pain. Endoscopy reveals a shallow sharply demarcated ulcer in the gastric antrum. Biopsy findings include lymphocyte, macrophage, and plasma cell infiltration, along with granulation tissue formation and fibrosis. What term best describes the type of inflammation observed in this man?","explanation":"In the context of a gastric antrum ulcer, chronic inflammation is a common feature associated with conditions such as chronic gastritis.\r\n\r\n**Chronic inflammation** is characterized by the presence of immune cells including **lymphocytes** and **macrophages**. Structural changes such as **fibrosis** and granulation tissue are often seen in long-standing or persistent inflammatory conditions, as seen in this case.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nFibrinous inflammation involves the deposition of fibrin and is typically seen in more acute settings such as severe injury or inflammation.\r\n\r\nAcute inflammation is characterized by the rapid onset of immune cell infiltration and vascular changes. The presence of granulation tissue and fibrosis in the biopsy findings suggests a more prolonged or chronic inflammatory process.\r\n\r\nGranulomatous inflammation involves the formation of granulomas, which are aggregates of immune cells.\r\n\r\n Serous inflammation involves the exudation of a watery, protein-rich fluid.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 96.","responses":[{"text":"Acute","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Granulomatous","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16265,"text":"What does the membrane attack complex (MAC) formed during complement activation consist of?","explanation":"The **membrane attack complex** (MAC) formed during complement activation consists of a sequence of complement proteins, including **C5b, C6, C7, C8,** and **C9**.\r\n\r\nThe assembly of the membrane attack complex MAC begins with the activation of the complement cascade. C5b initiates the formation of the MAC, and subsequent binding of C6, C7, C8, and multiple units of C9 results in the creation of a **transmembrane channel** or pore, leading to cell membrane disruption and cell lysis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 91.","responses":[{"text":"C5b, C6, C7, C8, and C9","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"C1, C2, C4 and C6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C5a and C5b","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C1, C3b, and C4b","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C3a, C3b, and C5b","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16266,"text":"What initiates the classical pathway of complement activation?","explanation":"The **classical pathway** of complement activation is **initiated** by the formation of **antigen-antibody complexes**. When antibodies (particularly IgM or IgG) bind to antigens on the surface of pathogens, they can activate the classical complement pathway.\r\n\r\nThe binding of antibodies to antigens results in conformational changes that allow the recruitment and activation of C1. The activated C1 then cleaves C4 and C2, forming the classical pathway C3 convertase (C4b2a), leading to further downstream complement activation.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe binding of mannose-binding lectin (MBL) to microbial surfaces is involved in the lectin pathway, not the classical pathway.\r\n\r\nThe breakdown of C3 occurs in both the classical and alternative pathways after the formation of C3 convertase. However, it is not the initiation step of the classical pathway.\r\n\r\nWhile the binding of C-reactive protein (CRP) to microbial surfaces is involved in the activation of the classical complement pathway, the initial step in the classical pathway is the formation of antigen-antibody complexes.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 90.","responses":[{"text":"Antigen-antibody complexes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Binding of mannose-binding lectin (MBL) to microbial surfaces","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Breakdown of C3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Binding of C-reactive protein (CRP) to microbial surfaces","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of C3 convertase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16267,"text":"Which of the following is correct regarding the inflammation in a 65-year-old man with a 5-year history of osteoarthritis?","explanation":"In **osteoarthritis**, the inflammation is generally considered to be a part of the repair process rather than a typical inflammatory response seen in conditions like rheumatoid arthritis.  **Inflammation** in osteoarthritis is characterized by the presence of **alternatively activated macrophages** that are involved in **tissue repair**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nGranuloma formation is not a characteristic feature of osteoarthritis. Granulomas are more commonly associated with conditions such as granulomatosis with polyangiitis.\r\n\r\nCytokines and growth factors play a crucial role in the inflammatory response associated with osteoarthritis. They are involved in the regulation of inflammation and tissue repair.\r\n\r\nOsteoarthritis typically does not present with a neutrophilic exudate or pus formation. Neutrophils are more commonly associated with acute inflammatory conditions.\r\n\r\nWhile osteoarthritis is primarily a non-inflammatory condition, low-grade inflammation can occur, and the presence of plasma cells and B lymphocytes is not entirely ruled out. However, they are typically associated with autoimmune inflammatory arthritis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 97.","responses":[{"text":"Cytokines and growth factors having no role in this type of inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Granuloma formation as a constant feature in these patients","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophilic exudate with pus formation on biopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alternatively activated macrophages promoting tissue repair","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma cells and B lymphocytes being almost never found","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16268,"text":"Complement deficiencies lead to an increased risk of which of the following?","explanation":"**Complement deficiencies** can lead to an increased risk of **bacterial infections**. The complement system is a crucial part of the innate immune system, and its activation contributes to the elimination of pathogens, particularly bacteria. Individuals with complement deficiencies may be more susceptible to recurrent or severe bacterial infections, especially those caused by encapsulated bacteria.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHypersensitivity reactions involve an exaggerated immune response to certain antigens.\r\n\r\nAllergic reactions involve immune responses mediated by IgE antibodies and other immune cells.\r\n\r\nWhile complement activation plays a role in immune complex clearance and regulation of the immune response, complement deficiencies are not a direct cause of autoimmune diseases.\r\n\r\nHypergammaglobulinemia refers to elevated levels of immunoglobulins in the blood.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 92.","responses":[{"text":"Allergic reactions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypergammaglobulinemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autoimmune diseases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypersensitivity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacterial infections","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16269,"text":"What is the involvement of the major histocompatibility complex (MHC)?","explanation":"The **major histocompatibility complex** (MHC), also known as the human leukocyte antigen (HLA) system in humans, plays a crucial role in the immune system. Its primary involvement is in the process of **transplant rejection**.\r\n\r\nMHC molecules present antigens to T cells, which are key players in the immune response. During organ transplantation, MHC compatibility between the donor and recipient is crucial. **Incompatibility**, or the presence of foreign MHC antigens, can trigger an immune response leading to rejection of the transplanted organ.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nMHC is not directly involved in hormone regulation. It is primarily associated with immune responses, particularly in antigen presentation to T cells.\r\n\r\nBlood clotting is regulated by a complex cascade of proteins, including clotting factors and platelets.\r\n\r\nMuscle contraction is regulated by the proteins actin and myosin.\r\n\r\nNeurotransmitter release at synapses is regulated by neuronal processes and specific proteins involved in vesicle fusion and release.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 236-237.","responses":[{"text":"Muscle contraction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood clotting","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neurotransmitter release","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hormone regulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transplant rejection","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16270,"text":"In a normal distribution curve, what percentage of the curve is represented by the shaded area under the curve with ±1 SD (plus minus one standard deviation around the mean) on either side of the mean value?","explanation":"In a **normal distribution**, approximately **68%** of the data falls within one standard deviation (**±1 SD**) on either side of the mean. This is known as the **empirical rule** or the 68-95-99.7 rule, where:\r\n\r\n- Approximately 68% of the data falls within ±1 standard deviation\r\n- Approximately 95% falls within ±2 standard deviations\r\n- Approximately 99.7% falls within ±3 standard deviations","reference":"The normal distribution - Sociology 3112 - Department of Sociology - the University of Utah. Accessed June 23, 2023. https://soc.utah.edu/sociology3112/normal-distribution.php","responses":[{"text":"45%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"13%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"68%","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"27%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"50%","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16271,"text":"What does sterilization refer to?","explanation":"**Sterilization** refers to the process of **killing** or removing **all forms of microbial life**, including bacteria, viruses, fungi, and spores. It aims to achieve a state of complete absence of viable microorganisms, ensuring the complete elimination of microbial contamination.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nSterilization encompasses the elimination of both bacteria and viruses, along with other microorganisms.\r\n\r\nRemoving visible dirt from a surface It does not achieve the level of microbial elimination seen in sterilization.\r\n\r\nDisinfection aims to reduce the microbial load to a safe level","reference":"Introductiondisinfection \u0026 sterilization guidelines | guidelines library | infection control | cdc. Published April 4, 2019. Accessed June 23, 2023. https://www.cdc.gov/infectioncontrol/guidelines/disinfection/introduction.html","responses":[{"text":"Reducing the number of microorganisms to a safe level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Removing visible dirt from a surface","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Killing or removing all forms of microbial life","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Killing bacteria but not viruses","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inactivating viruses on a surface","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16272,"text":"What is the most resistant form of microbial life to physical and chemical agents?","explanation":"**Bacterial endospores** are highly resistant structures formed by certain bacteria, such as _Clostridium_ and _Bacillus_ species, as a protective mechanism in response to adverse environmental conditions.\r\n\r\nBacterial endospores have a unique structure with multiple layers, including a tough outer coat and a thick cortex, which provides **resistance** against **heat**, **chemicals**, **radiation**, and **desiccation**. This resilience allows bacterial endospores to withstand harsh conditions that would otherwise be lethal to vegetative bacterial cells.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nBacterial endospores are generally more resistant to a broader range of conditions than fungal spores, gram-negative bacteria, protozoan cysts, and viruses.","reference":"6. 12c: relative resistance of microbes. Biology LibreTexts. Published May 11, 2017. Accessed June 23, 2023. https://bio.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Microbiology/Microbiology_(Boundless)/06%3A_Culturing_Microorganisms/6.12%3A_Control_in_Microbial_Death/6.12C%3A_Relative_Resistance_of_Microbes","responses":[{"text":"Viruses","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gram-negative bacteria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fungal spores","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacterial endospores","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Protozoan cysts","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16273,"text":"What do agents referred to as \"bactericidal\" do?","explanation":"Agents referred to as **bactericidal** have the **capability to kill bacteria**. These agents directly lead to the death of bacterial cells, reducing their viability and eliminating the bacterial population.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAgents that inactivate bacterial toxins are often referred to as antitoxins.\r\n\r\nAgents that inhibit bacterial growth are termed bacteriostatic. \r\n\r\nThe removal of bacteria from a surface refers to physical methods or agents that mechanically remove bacteria from surfaces, such as cleaning or washing. It does not necessarily involve killing the bacteria.\r\n\r\nAgents preventing bacterial attachment typically target adhesion mechanisms but may not necessarily lead to bacterial cell death. They aim to inhibit the initial steps of bacterial colonization.","reference":"Whalen K, Finkel R, Panavelil TA. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 6th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2015: 473.","responses":[{"text":"Inhibit bacterial growth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inactivate bacterial toxins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Remove bacteria from the surface","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kill bacteria","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prevent bacterial attachment","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16274,"text":"A 19-year-old woman came into the medical outpatient department with a history of frequent nosebleeds and increased menstrual flow. On physical examination, petechiae and purpura are present on the skin of her extremities. Laboratory studies show normal partial thromboplastin time (APTT), prothrombin time (PT), platelet count, and decreased von Willebrand factor activity. This patient most likely has a derangement in which of the following steps in hemostasis?","explanation":"The patient's clinical presentation with frequent nosebleeds, increased menstrual flow, petechiae, and purpura, along with decreased von Willebrand factor activity, suggests a deficiency or **dysfunction in platelet adhesion**.\r\n\r\nVon Willebrand factor (vWF) plays a crucial role in platelet adhesion by binding to platelets and collagen in the blood vessel wall. This process is essential for the initial step of hemostasis, where platelets adhere to the site of vascular injury.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nPlatelet aggregation occurs after platelet adhesion and involves the formation of stable platelet plugs. The patient's presentation suggests a defect in the earlier step of platelet adhesion.\r\n\r\nProthrombin generation occurs in the coagulation cascade and involves the conversion of prothrombin to thrombin. Normal prothrombin time (PT) and partial thromboplastin time (APTT) in the laboratory studies indicate that prothrombin generation is likely intact.\r\n\r\nVasoconstriction is the initial response to vascular injury and is not directly related to the patient's symptoms or laboratory findings.\r\n\r\nProthrombin inhibition is part of the anticoagulant system and is not likely to be the cause of the patient's symptoms, given the normal laboratory studies and the nature of her bleeding manifestations.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 667-668.","responses":[{"text":"Vasoconstriction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelet adhesion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prothrombin generation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelet aggregation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prothrombin inhibition","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16277,"text":"A 23-year-old pregnant woman has macrocytic anemia, an increased serum concentration of transferrin, and a normal serum concentration of vitamin B12. The most likely cause of her anemia is a deficiency of which of the following?","explanation":"The combination of macrocytic anemia, **increased serum transferrin** concentration, and a normal serum concentration of vitamin B12 suggests a **deficiency of folic acid**.\r\n\r\nFolic acid is essential for DNA synthesis and is crucial for the maturation of red blood cells. Its deficiency can result in impaired DNA synthesis, leading to **macrocytic anemia**. The increased transferrin concentration indicates an attempt by the body to compensate for the anemia by increasing iron transport capacity.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nIron deficiency is a common cause of microcytic anemia, not macrocytic anemia.\r\n\r\nWhile cobalamin deficiency can also cause macrocytic anemia, the normal serum concentration of vitamin B12 in this case rules out cobalamin deficiency.\r\n\r\nDeficiency of intrinsic factor leads to pernicious anemia, characterized by a decrease in vitamin B12 absorption. However, this patient has normal levels of vitamin B12.\r\n\r\nErythropoietin deficiency typically leads to normocytic anemia and is not associated with an increased serum transferrin concentration.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 654.","responses":[{"text":"Iron","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Folic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intrinsic factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cobalamin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythropoietin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16278,"text":"A 20-year-old woman presents to her primary care physician with heavy menstrual bleeding. Her physician prescribes tranexamic acid. What is tranexamic acid's mechanism of action?","explanation":"**Tranexamic acid** is an **antifibrinolytic** used to reduce excessive bleeding. Its primary mechanism of action is the **inhibition of plasminogen activation**, leading to a reduction in fibrinolysis.\r\n\r\nPlasminogen is converted to **plasmin**, which is responsible for breaking down blood clots. By inhibiting plasminogen activation, tranexamic acid helps stabilize blood clots and prevents their premature breakdown, particularly in conditions associated with excessive bleeding, such as heavy menstrual bleeding.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nTranexamic acid does not activate platelets. Instead, it works by inhibiting fibrinolysis, which is the process of breaking down blood clots.\r\n\r\nThe suppression of the luteinizing hormone (LH) surge is not a mechanism of tranexamic acid. LH is primarily involved in the regulation of the menstrual cycle.\r\n\r\nTranexamic acid inhibits the activation of plasminogen rather than activating it, preventing the conversion to plasmin and, consequently, reducing fibrinolysis.\r\n\r\nBlocking cyclooxygenase is the mechanism of action of nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), not tranexamic acid.","reference":"Whalen K, Finkel R, Panavelil TA. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 6th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2015: 307.","responses":[{"text":"Activates plasminogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blocks cyclooxygenase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activates platelets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suppresses LH surge","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits plasmin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16279,"text":"A medical study is conducted to estimate the prevalence of hypertension amongst a defined population and evaluate people of different ages, ethnicities, geographical locations, and social backgrounds. Which one of the following options best describes the type of study design most appropriate for the above study?","explanation":"The study described, aiming to estimate the prevalence of hypertension and evaluate people of different ages, ethnicities, geographical locations, and social backgrounds, is best characterized as a **cross-sectional study**.\r\n\r\nIn a cross-sectional study, data is collected at a **single point in time** from individuals within a **defined population** or group. This type of study is suitable for assessing the prevalence of a condition (in this case, hypertension) and exploring the distribution of the condition among different subgroups based on factors such as age, ethnicity, geography, and social background.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nA correlational study investigates the relationship between two or more variables but does not necessarily involve different subgroups or the assessment of prevalence.\r\n\r\nCase-control studies are retrospective and compare individuals with a particular condition (cases) to those without the condition (controls) to identify factors associated with the condition. This design is not ideal for estimating prevalence.\r\n\r\nCohort studies follow a group of individuals over time to assess the development of outcomes. In this scenario, the emphasis is on estimating prevalence at a specific point rather than following individuals longitudinally.\r\n\r\nA case series is a descriptive study that involves the collection and presentation of information about individuals with a similar condition. It does not involve a comparison group or assessment of prevalence in a defined population.","reference":"Cross-sectional study - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 23, 2023. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/pharmacology-toxicology-and-pharmaceutical-science/cross-sectional-study","responses":[{"text":"Correlational","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cohort","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Case-series","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cross-sectional","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Case-control","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16280,"text":"In a study that began in 2001, a group of 3500 adults in Islamabad were asked about\r\nalcohol consumption. The occurrence of cases of liver cancer between 2018-2023 was\r\nstudied in this group. What is the above study design?","explanation":"The described study design is a **cohort study**. In a cohort study, a group of individuals (the cohort) is followed over time to observe the occurrence of outcomes or events.\r\n\r\nIn a cohort study, researchers can assess the relationship between **exposure variables** (such as alcohol consumption) and the development of **outcomes** (such as liver cancer) over a **specified period**. Cohort studies are particularly useful for investigating the association between exposures and outcomes and establishing temporality.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nA case series involves the collection and analysis of detailed information about a group of patients with a similar diagnosis, usually focusing on clinical or pathological features.\r\n\r\nCorrelational studies examine the relationship between two or more variables without manipulating them. However, the given study involves following a group of individuals over time, making it a cohort study.\r\n\r\nCross-sectional studies collect data from participants at a single point in time, providing a snapshot of a population.\r\n\r\nIn a case-control study, individuals with a particular condition (cases) are compared to those without the condition (controls) to identify factors associated with the disease.","reference":"Barrett D, Noble H. What are cohort studies? Evidence-Based Nursing. 2019;22(4):95-96. doi:10.1136/ebnurs-2019-103183","responses":[{"text":"Case series","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cross-sectional","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cohort","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Correlational","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Case-control","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16281,"text":"A research paper states that: \"To access the frequency of mood disorders among medical students of Karachi.\" Which of the following best describes the statement in the above scenario?","explanation":"In the given statement, the phrase \"To assess the frequency of mood disorders among medical students of Karachi,\" represents the **objective** of the research. The objective outlines the specific goal or **purpose of the study**, indicating what the researchers aim to achieve or investigate.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe rationale would provide the reasons or justification for conducting the study. It explains why the research is important and what knowledge gaps it aims to fill.\r\n\r\nOperational definitions clarify how certain variables will be measured or manipulated in the study. They specify how concepts will be observed or measured.\r\n\r\nA hypothesis is a testable statement predicting the outcome of the research. It suggests a relationship between variables and provides a basis for investigation.\r\n\r\nThe topic is the general subject or area of interest for the research. It is broader than the objective and does not specify the purpose or goal of the study.","reference":"Formulating research aims and objectives. Research-Methodology. Accessed June 23, 2023. https://research-methodology.net/research-methodology/research-aims-and-objectives/","responses":[{"text":"Operational definitions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rationale","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Topic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Objective","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16282,"text":"In a small study, 12 women with ovarian cancer and 12 women with no apparent disease were asked whether they had ever used estrogen. Each woman with cancer was matched by age, race, weight, and parity to a woman without disease. Identify the study design.","explanation":null,"reference":"Case-control study - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 23, 2023. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/biochemistry-genetics-and-molecular-biology/case-control-study","responses":[{"text":"Case-control","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Case report","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cross-sectional","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ecological","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cohort","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16283,"text":"\"Like cases should be treated as like, and the benefits and the risks associated with research must be allocated equitably across patients.\" Which of the following best expresses this principle of medical ethics?","explanation":"The principle of **justice** in medical ethics emphasizes the fair distribution of benefits and burdens in society. The statement \"Like cases should be treated as like, and the benefits and the risks associated with research must be allocated equitably across patients\" aligns most closely with the principle of justice.\r\n\r\nJustice involves **treating individuals fairly** and ensuring that similar cases are treated similarly. In this context, the statement emphasizes the **equitable** allocation of benefits and risks in research, reflecting the principle of justice.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nBeneficence refers to the duty to promote the well-being and best interests of the patient.\r\n\r\nAutonomy pertains to respecting individuals' rights to make their own decisions.\r\n\r\nWhile the concept of treating individuals fairly is related to equality, the principle of justice is a more specific ethical framework that addresses the distribution of benefits and risks.\r\n\r\nNon-maleficence emphasizes the duty to not harm the patient.","reference":"Varkey B. Principles of clinical ethics and their application to practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119","responses":[{"text":"Autonomy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beneficence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Justice","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Equality","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-maleficence","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16284,"text":"A group of medical students started researching the health issues and quality of life of commercial sex workers. For data collection, they would have to go to various unsuitable places. They spent a year trying to collect data but enrolled a dozen participants. They became discouraged and left the study altogether. Which of the following options best describes the factor ignored by the students while deciding the research topic?","explanation":"**Feasibility** refers to the practicality and likelihood of successfully conducting a study given the available resources, time, and conditions. In this case, the students did not consider whether their research, which involved going to unsuitable places to collect data on commercial sex workers, was **practical** and **achievable**.\r\n\r\nIgnoring feasibility can lead to challenges in data collection, recruitment, and overall study completion. In this scenario, the students faced difficulties in enrolling participants and collecting data due to the impractical nature of their research approach.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nMagnitude refers to the extent or scale of a health issue.\r\n\r\nEconomics involves the financial aspect of a research study.\r\n\r\nPreventability refers to the extent to which health issues can be avoided or mitigated. \r\n\r\n Politics involves the influence of political factors on health issues.","reference":"What is the difference between feasibility studies and pilot testing? Research Office. Published May 4, 2015. Accessed June 24, 2023. https://research.oregonstate.edu/irb/what-difference-between-feasibility-studies-and-pilot-testing","responses":[{"text":"Economics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Preventability","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Feasibility","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnitude","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Politics","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16285,"text":"A researcher of a new drug trial informed the volunteers about the possible benefits of a new drug under trial in that study. She deliberately laid more emphasis on the possible benefits of the drug under trial and avoided discussion of the possible adverse effects of the drug to enrolled participants to increase participation. Which of the following identifies the central ethical principle lacking in the above scenario?","explanation":null,"reference":"Varkey B. Principles of clinical ethics and their application to practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119","responses":[{"text":"Beneficence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Justice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-maleficence","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Informed consent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Confidentiality","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16287,"text":"A 25-year-old male patient presents with a history of irrelevant talks, anger, and suspicion towards family members, had a big fight with the family, and injured the younger with an iron rod. He has been brought to you for treatment. Which of the following would you consider before initiating an interview with him?","explanation":"In a situation where a patient presents with a history of aggression, anger, and violent behavior, it is essential to prioritize the **safety** of both the patient and the healthcare provider. Before initiating an interview, it is crucial to **inquire about any dangerous objects with the patient**.\r\n\r\nIdentifying potentially dangerous objects, such as weapons or items that could be used for self-harm or harm to others, is a necessary precaution. This information helps in assessing the level of risk and implementing appropriate safety measures.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nRestraint should be used as a last resort in accordance with ethical and legal guidelines. Forceful restraint without proper assessment may escalate the situation and is not the initial step.\r\n\r\nSedation should be used judiciously and only when necessary for the safety of the patient or others. Immediate sedation without a thorough assessment is not the preferred initial approach.\r\n\r\nWhile involving the family in the patient's care is important, if there is an immediate risk of harm, simply asking the family to leave may not be sufficient.\r\n\r\nWaiting for a violent reaction without taking proactive measures is not an appropriate approach. Safety precautions should be implemented before any potential escalation.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Blood module, Subject: Behavioral sciences; Topic: Psychiatric Interview; Sub-topic: Precaution Of Any Dangerousness Before Starting an Interview.","responses":[{"text":"Inquire about any danger objects with the patient","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ask the staff to hold the patient and sedate him immediately","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Talk to the family and ask them to leave the patient alone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Talk to the security guard and restraint the patient forcefully","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wait for the patient's violent reaction to happen in the ward","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16288,"text":"During the case discussion in the ward, you noticed that the safety measures in place for your junior doctor, who is responsible for taking psychiatric history from a violent patient, are inadequate.  What would you advise your junior doctor?","explanation":"Ensuring the **safety** of both the patient and healthcare providers is of paramount importance, especially when dealing with potentially violent or aggressive patients. If you notice inadequate safety measures in place for your junior doctor, the most appropriate course of action is to **postpone the interview** until all safety measures have been ensured.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nIgnoring the family's account and potential safety concerns is not appropriate. Family input can provide valuable information, and safety measures should be prioritized.\r\n\r\nSafety is always a priority in healthcare settings. Balancing safety with providing care for the patient's illness is essential, and both aspects should be addressed appropriately.\r\n\r\nReassurance is important, but not at the expense of safety. Advising to take a complete history without addressing safety concerns is not advisable.\r\n\r\nDelaying the interview for an arbitrary period without addressing safety concerns is not a responsible approach.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Blood module, Subject: Behavioral sciences; Topic: Psychiatric Interview; Sub-topic: Precaution Of Any Dangerousness Before Starting an Interview.","responses":[{"text":"Safety is not important as compared to the patient's illness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reassure your junior doctor and ask her to take a complete history","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ignore the family’s account of the patient and his violent acts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Postpone the interview until all safety measures have been ensured","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Wait for 72 hours to take the history from the patient","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16290,"text":"A 22-year-old male presented to the outpatient department with a complaint of swelling in the neck region for 10-12 days. He does not give any history of flu or sore throat. Physical examination revealed right anterior cervical lymph nodes, about 1.0 cm in size., soft, non-tender, and mobile i.e. not fixed. The spleen is also enlarged. There is no other positive finding. What should be the next step in the management of this patient?","explanation":"The patient's presentation with painless, **enlarged cervical lymph nodes** along with **splenomegaly** warrants further investigation to determine the underlying cause. Considering the persistence of symptoms for 10-12 days in the absence of flu or sore throat symptoms, a **lymph node biopsy** is the most appropriate next step in the management of this patient.\r\n\r\nKey features suggesting the need for a biopsy include the size of the lymph nodes, their consistency (soft), non-tender nature, and the presence of splenomegaly. These characteristics raise concern for an underlying lymphoproliferative disorder such as lymphoma.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile investigating for viral infections is important, the persistent nature of the symptoms, along with the presence of splenomegaly, makes it prudent to consider a lymph node biopsy rather than viral serology.\r\n\r\nGiven the absence of flu or sore throat symptoms and the persistent nature of the swelling, empirical antibiotic or antiviral therapy is not the best first-line approach.\r\n\r\nGiven the concerning features of persistent painless cervical lymphadenopathy and splenomegaly, reassurance without further investigation is not appropriate.\r\n\r\nThe persistence of symptoms and the presence of splenomegaly make a prompt diagnostic evaluation, such as a lymph node biopsy, more appropriate than simple observation in this case.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Blood module, Subject: Behavioral sciences; Topic: History and Clinical Findings Of Lymphadenopathy and Splenomegaly; Sub-topic: Diagnostic Approach, Investigations.","responses":[{"text":"Lymph node biopsy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Reassure the patient and send him home","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antibiotics/antivirals","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Observe the patient for 3-4 weeks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Send viral serology/VDRL/PCR","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16291,"text":"Hemostasis is the natural process that stops blood loss when an injury occurs. Which of the following bleeding manifestations or associations suggests secondary hemostatic disorder?","explanation":"Bleeding into joints (**hemarthrosis**) is a hallmark of **secondary hemostatic disorders**.\r\n\r\nHemostasis involves a series of steps that collectively prevent and stop bleeding. Secondary hemostasis refers to the coagulation cascade, where clotting factors come into play. Bleeding manifestations associated with secondary hemostatic disorders often involve deficiencies or dysfunction of **clotting factors**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile nosebleeds can be caused by various factors, they are not specifically indicative of a secondary hemostatic disorder. Epistaxis can result from local factors such as trauma or inflammation.\r\n\r\nBruising can be related to either primary hemostatic disorders (platelet dysfunction or vascular abnormalities) or secondary hemostatic disorders. However, it is not specific to secondary hemostasis.\r\n\r\nMucocutaneous bleed refers to bleeding from mucosal surfaces and the skin. It can occur in both primary and secondary hemostatic disorders and is not exclusive to secondary hemostatic disorders.\r\n\r\nDistensible skin and lax joints are commonly seen in Ehlers-Danlos syndrome, a genetic disorder affecting collagen synthesis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 667.","responses":[{"text":"Distensible skin and lax joints","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemarthrosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bruising","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epistaxis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mucocutaneous bleed","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16292,"text":"A 65-year-old male presents with a 2 months history of fever, lethargy, and night\r\nsweats. On physical examination, he has palpable cervical and axillary lymph nodes. The spleen is palpable 2 cm below the left costal margin. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Lymphomas** are malignancies of the lymphatic system, and they often present with **painless lymphadenopathy** and systemic symptoms such as **fever** and **weight loss**.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the presence of palpable cervical and axillary lymph nodes along with splenomegaly, raises suspicion of systemic lymphoma. The spleen's involvement is common in lymphomas, and its enlargement (**splenomegaly**) is detected by palpation below the left costal margin.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile malaria can cause fever and splenomegaly, the chronicity of symptoms and the presence of palpable lymph nodes are more suggestive of a chronic lymphoproliferative disorder.\r\n\r\nViral infections can present with fever and lethargy, but the persistent nature of the symptoms and the presence of palpable lymph nodes and splenomegaly make lymphoma a more likely diagnosis.\r\n\r\nWhile metastatic cancer can cause generalized symptoms, the characteristic lymphadenopathy and splenomegaly seen in this patient are more indicative of a primary lymphoid malignancy like lymphoma.\r\n\r\nChronic myeloid leukemia (CML) can present with splenomegaly, but the extensive lymph node involvement and prominent lymphadenopathy are not typical for CML.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Blood module, Subject: Medicine; Topic: History and Clinical Findings Of Lymphadenopathy and Splenomegaly; Sub-topic: Diagnostic Approach, Drainage and Etiology of Lymphadenopathy.","responses":[{"text":"Viral fever","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic myeloid leukemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic malaria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metastatic cancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphoma","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16293,"text":"A 62-year-old woman complains of fatigue and numbness in her arms and legs for 1 month and takes thyroid replacement therapy for hypothyroidism. She has a long history of diarrhea on and off. A complete blood count (CBC) shows white blood cells (WBC) 3.8x10^9/L (normal: 4.0 to 11 x 10^9/L), hemoglobin (Hb) 8g/dL (normal: 12 to 16g/dL), hematocrit (Hct) 27 percent (normal: 36 to 46 percent), mean corpuscular volume (MCV) 120 fL (normal: 80 to 100fL), and platelets 115x109/L (normal: 150 to 400x10^9/L). She is diagnosed as a case of megaloblastic anemia with vitamin B12 deficiency. Which of the following autoantibodies is most likely present in this patient?","explanation":"The autoantibodies that are most likely to be present in this case are **anti-intrinsic factor antibodies**. These antibodies target intrinsic factor - a protein necessary for the absorption of vitamin B12 in the terminal ileum.\r\n\r\nVitamin B12 deficiency and megaloblastic anemia in a patient with a thyroid disorder point towards an autoimmune cause, specifically **pernicious anemia**. Pernicious anemia is often seen in older individuals and is characterized by chronic atrophic gastritis, which can lead to **vitamin B12 malabsorption**, as indicated by the patient's history of chronic diarrhea.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAntigliadin antibodies are associated with celiac disease. Celiac disease is more commonly associated with iron deficiency anemia.\r\n\r\nAntismooth muscle antibodies are often seen in autoimmune hepatitis, which typically presents with jaundice and abdominal pain.\r\n\r\nAntimitochondrial antibodies are characteristic of primary biliary cirrhosis, which typically presents with jaundice, splenomegaly, and abdominal pain.\r\n\r\nAnticentromere antibodies are commonly found in CREST syndrome, which is characterized by calcinosis, Raynaud phenomenon, esophageal dysmotility, sclerodactyly, and telangiectasia.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 654.","responses":[{"text":"Antigliadin antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antimitochondrial antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anticentromere antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti-intrinsic factor antibodies","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Antismooth muscle antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16294,"text":"Which of the following is a characteristic of megaloblastic anemia?","explanation":"**Megaloblastic anemia** is characterized by the presence of large, immature red blood cell precursors in the bone marrow, known as megaloblasts. Ineffective erythropoiesis in megaloblastic anemia leads to the accumulation of these abnormal cells, contributing to the **hypercellularity** observed on **bone marrow examination**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nIron levels are generally normal or increased in megaloblastic anemia.\r\n\r\nIn megaloblastic anemia, the reticulocyte count is usually decreased, reflecting ineffective erythropoiesis. The immature cells produced are not efficiently released into the bloodstream.\r\n\r\nTotal iron-binding capacity (TIBC) is often normal or decreased in megaloblastic anemia.\r\n\r\nIn megaloblastic anemia, serum vitamin B12 levels are decreased, as the condition is often a result of a deficiency in this vitamin.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 652.","responses":[{"text":"Bone marrow will be hypercellular","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum iron will be reduced","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reticulocyte count will be increased","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum vitamin B12 will be increased","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"TIBC will be increased","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

